{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Washington, D.C., United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.\n| width           = \n| image           = National Gallery of Art (49656625722).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Visitors wearing masks in the [[National Gallery of Art]], the day before it closed as a precaution against COVID-19\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| first_case      = March 7, 2020\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 902\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| deaths          = 21\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.dc.gov/}}\n}}\n\nThe first cases of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[Washington, D.C.]] were reported on March 7, 2020. {{As of|2020|04|02|df=US}}, there are 902 confirmed cases and 21 deaths in Washington, D.C. alone, with other cases in the surrounding counties of the [[Washington metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"dcgovdata\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Data |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |website=DC.Gov |publisher=Government of the District of Columbia |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134324/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Washington, D.C. medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February ===\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] signed an executive order that began to prepare Washington D.C. for coronavirus impacts on February 28. It was announced in the executive order that the District's Emergency Operations Center (EOC) would be activated on March 2, 2020 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to begin to \"coordinate inter-agency information sharing and identify logistical needs for critical incident responses.\" It was also announced that the Washington D.C. Department of Health and the Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency would be responsible for the response planning for COVID-19.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|title=Mayor's Order: District Government Preparations for the Coronavirus {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329193351/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n\n==== March 1\u20134 ====\nOn March 2 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m., the D.C. Emergency Operations Center was activated at an Enhanced Watch status, as per the executive order signed on February 28.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 3, Mayor Bowser, the D.C. Department of Health, and the D.C. Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency held a public briefing on the coronavirus and the District's \"monitoring, preparation, and response\" to it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|title=Mayor Bowser to Hold Briefing on the District's Coronavirus Monitoring, Preparation, and Response {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004155/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 5\u20137====\nOn March 7, the first two cases of COVID-19 in Washington, D.C. were confirmed. The first case was a [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] at [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]] who had not traveled outside the United States recently or had contact with another infected coronavirus patient. He participated in church services on February 23 and March 1. The rector felt better initially, but his condition deteriorated to the point of hospitalization, when it was confirmed he had coronavirus. After it was confirmed the rector contracted the virus, the church cancelled services indefinitely. The second case was a [[Nigeria]]n national who traveled to D.C. and went to a hospital in [[Maryland]] for treatment. Although the second man was being treated at a Maryland hospital, he was counted as the District's second case by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Georgetown Church Rector, Traveler Diagnosed as DC's First 2 Coronavirus Cases |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=NBC4 Washington |date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154326/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1236422174958895104|title=Late this afternoon, testing at the Public Health Lab at the DC Department of Forensic Sciences yielded its first presumptive positive coronavirus (COVID-19) case. Join me live at 7:30 p.m. for a briefing at the John A. Wilson Building.|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 8\u201310====\nOn March 9, [[School Without Walls (Washington, D.C.)|School Without Walls]], a public school in [[Foggy Bottom]], was closed by [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) for a full-day deep cleaning and disinfecting by a third-party contractor after an employee was exposed to COVID-19 the week before. The employee tested negative and entered a two-week quarantine. DCPS chancellor Lewis Ferebee announced the closing over Twitter the previous day.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1236819215920832513|date=8 Mar 2020|title=Tomorrow - 3/9 - School Without Walls High School will be closed. DCPS is conducting a deep cleaning and disinfecting of the building following an employee being exposed to COVID-19. Test results were negative, and there is no immediate risk to students and staff. cc: @SWWHSA}}</ref>\n\nThree more coronavirus cases in D.C. were confirmed the night of March 9, including an attendee of Christ Church Georgetown. D.C. officials recommended a two-week self-quarantine per CDC guidelines for anyone who attended Christ Church on February 24 or between February 28 and March 3. At that time, $1.5 million had been allocated to the pandemic response by the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gelman |first1=Scott |last2=Alvarez |first2=Alejandro |title=16 coronavirus cases confirmed in DC, Md. and Va. |url=https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=WTOP |date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313023822/https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[George Washington University]] announced classes will be moved online after spring break, starting on March 23 and continuing until at least April 5. In addition, all residential students were expected to no longer be living on campus beginning March 21. It was stated that an opening date would not be announced until the end of the instructional continuity period when a decision for the rest of the semester would be made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|title=George Washington University moving to online classes after spring break|date=2020-03-10|website=Fox 5 DC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311103004/https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Resource Center|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312130006/https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso on March 10, [[Georgetown Day School]], a private school, closed indefinitely and began a deep clean citing concerns about community members affiliated with [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volou |first1=Khalida |title=DC school closed due to coronavirus exposure linked to Christ Church Georgetown |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |agency=WUSA9 |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311195837/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 11\u201314====\nOn March 11, [[Maria Cantwell]], a U.S. senator from Washington state, closed her D.C. office due to one of her aides testing positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|title=Aide to Maria Cantwell tests positive for coronavirus. Senator closes her D.C. office|last=Lightman|first=David|website=thenewstribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313030257/https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|archive-date=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Georgetown University]] announced that it would be moving to virtual learning entirely beginning on March 16, and while campus would remain open and key services would remain accessible the university strongly suggested that students return to their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khan |first1=Saliqa |title=Georgetown University moves to virtual learning amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |work=WUSA9 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318192012/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the [[United States Capitol]], the [[White House]], and the [[United States Supreme Court Building]] closed to most of the public until April after several offices closed and multiple lawmakers went into precautionary quarantines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zengerle |first1=Patricia |last2=Heavey |first2=Susan |title=UPDATE 5-U.S. federal buildings put away the welcome mat as coronavirus hits |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-capitol/update-5-us-federal-buildings-put-away-the-welcome-mat-as-coronavirus-hits-idUSL1N2B50S4 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools|DCPS]] announced that they will cancel classes until April 1, implementing online distance learning.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1238430012417748993|date=13 March 2020|title=DCPS will modify operations from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31 to help limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. For more info about the closure schedule, meal locations for students & distance learning details, please visit: https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus}}</ref> Also on March 13, the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] (WMATA) escalated its operations to level 3 of its pandemic flu plan, announcing that service on the [[Washington Metro]] would be reduced to one train every 12 minutes from Monday to Saturday and one train every 15 minutes on Sunday beginning on March 17. In addition, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] service would change to a Saturday supplemental schedule on weekdays beginning on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|title=Metro takes additional steps, coordinates with public health authorities on COVID-19 {{!}} WMATA|website=wmata.com|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314155101/https://wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|archive-date=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|title=Metro to reduce transit service in response to the coronavirus outbreak|last=George|first=Justin|date=13 March 2020|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134151/https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|archive-date=14 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] held a press conference, announcing that gatherings of people over 60 years of age or with preexisting health issues would be limited to 10 people. The restriction would not apply to residences, schools, or places of work. For populations not at-risk the government promoted [[social distancing]] measures to limit the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vitka |first1=Will |last2=Bonk |first2=Valerie |title=Trump declares national emergency; DC bans mass gatherings |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |work=WTOP |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314183154/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, Mayor Bowser issued a statement confirming 6 more positive cases in Washington, D.C., bringing the total number of cases up to 16.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 14 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316100728/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|archive-date=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 15\u201316====\nOn March 15, Bowser's office announced one more positive case in Washington D.C., bringing the total cumulative number of cases to 17. The patient in this case is a 38-year-old woman who came into contact with another case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 15|work=Government of the District of Columbia|accessdate=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324170918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Hill Restaurant Group (HRG) said on March 16 they would comply would restrictions on bars and restaurants ordered by Mayor Bowser on March 15. Tom Johnson, the managing director of the group, had earlier said he would ignore the order, saying it would force his company into bankruptcy.<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487826-dc-restaurant-group-says-it-will-comply-with-restrictions-after-mayor DC restaurant group says it will comply with restrictions after mayor's warning] The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn the evening of March 16, Mayor Bowser's office released an update that confirmed five more positive cases of coronavirus in the District. The patients involved were a 23-year-old man, a 42-year-old woman with a history of travel to Europe, a 54-year-old woman, a 54-year-old man, and a 56-year-old man. These five cases brought the cumulative number of cases in D.C. to 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 16 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317204518/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|archive-date=2020-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 17\u201318 ====\nLate on March 17, Mayor Bowser's office announced the confirmation of nine more positive cases in the District, bringing the total number of positive cases to 31. The patients were all male and between the ages of 23 and 61. The 23-year-old patient was confirmed to have attended the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[National Harbor, Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 17 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319072119/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|archive-date=2020-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, at least 8 more cases were found, including a [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department|DC FEMS]] employee (leading to a quarantine of 73 firefighters), a [[U.S. marshal]] at the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia]], and an undergraduate student at the George Washington University who lives off-campus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jack |title=Coronavirus: Jump in new cases around region; DC first responder, US Marshal test positive |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |work=WTOP |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002447/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia]] announced new [[social distancing]] precautions in dealing with callers reporting flu-like symptoms as well as changes to police protocol for citations and warning notices in light of the restriction of certain services in the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Metropolitan Police Department Operational Adjustments During COVID-19 |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002500/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== March 19\u201320 ====\nAs of March 19, the number of confirmed cases sharply jumped to 71 as the supply of tests was expanded, an increase of 32 over one day.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1240791217647976448|user=MayorBowser|title=As of 8:00 p.m. on Thursday, March 19, the District\u2019s coronavirus (COVID-19) data includes 32 new positive cases, bringing the District\u2019s overall positive case total to 71 individuals. For more information visit:|date=19 March 2020}}</ref> This includes two more DC FEMS members and an eight-year-old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |title=Coronavirus: As more tests become available, DC sees jump in coronavirus cases |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014753/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Washington Metro]] closed the [[Smithsonian station|Smithsonian]] and [[Arlington Cemetery station|Arlington Cemetery]] stations until further notice. Metro ridership reduced by 85% due to the pandemic, leading to general manager Paul Wiedefeld submitting a request to Congress for emergency funding.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Augenstein |first1=Neal |title=Coronavirus: Metro asks Congress for emergency funding after ridership drops 85% |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014754/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser announced the first death related to COVID-19 in the District, a 59-year-old male, Deacon Brother John-Sebastian Laird-Hammond, [[Order of Friars Minor|OFM]], a [[Franciscan]] [[friar]] and [[permanent deacon]], a native of [[Minonk, Illinois]], with underlying medical conditions, specifically a multi-year battle with a type of [[leukemia]] who had been undergoing cancer treatments and was therefore more vulnerable to the virus.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | title=A Franciscan friar and deacon is DC's first known coronavirus fatality | access-date=2020-03-26 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329041046/https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | archive-date=2020-03-29 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Bowser tweet first death\">{{cite tweet|last=Bowser |first=Muriel |author-link=Muriel Bowser |user=MayorBowser |number=1241051533631946752 |date=2020-03-20 |title=It is with great sadness that we announce a tragic death and, on behalf of our residents, I share our love and condolences with the patient\u2019s family and friends. |access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The number of cases rose to 77.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nDCPS extended the school shutdown to April 24, meaning classes would be scheduled to resume on Monday, April 27. In preparation for the beginning of distance learning on March 24, the DCPS Distance Learning platform was released, publicly accessible at {{URL|https://dcps.instructure.com/courses/179580}}. Certain schools would continue to provide lunch on weekdays.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1241081893656956931|title=\ud83d\udea8UPDATE\ud83d\udea8 DCPS will be closed to all staff and students through Friday, April 24 to help mitigate the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. Classes will resume for all students on Monday, April 27. For more info please visit: http://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus.|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21\u201322 ====\n\nOn March 21, the D.C. government, operating through the Metropolitan Police Department and the [[National Park Service]] announced several road closures around beginning on March 22, 7:00 AM to 8:00 PM, in an effort to reduce congregation of tourists around monuments during the [[National Cherry Blossom Festival]]. These crowds had not been conforming to social distancing guidelines and thus presented a possible vector for the transmission of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Corse |first1=Alexa |title=Washington, D.C., Closes Streets to Prevent Coronavirus Transmission |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213549/https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TRAFFIC ADVISORY: Street Closures |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213607/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[District of Columbia Department of Parks and Recreation|DC Department of Parks and Recreation]] closed all of its facilities including parks, playgrounds, and athletic fields. Only dog parks remained open.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1241457230349811712|user=DCDPR|title=!!ALERT - All DPR facilities including Playgrounds + Gated Parks and Athletic Fields are CLOSED. Dog parks remain open. Stay informed http://coronavirus.dc.gov.|date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] announced reduced operation from 325 routes to only 20 high-use corridors. Real-time bus data would no longer be available and drivers may bypass stops in order to observe social distancing guidelines on buses. [[WMATA]] said it hoped to restore some routes with limited operation hours soon.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delaney |first1=Matthew |title=Coronavirus: 2nd death in DC; cases surge throughout region with more testing |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |work=WTOP |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235143/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:30 PM that day was 98.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nOn March 22, the second death due to COVID-19 was reported in the District, a 65-year-old woman with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1241783602830020615|title=1/ I am saddened to announce a second death related to COVID-19 in our community. The hearts and prayers of our entire city are with her family and loved ones.|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:00 PM that day was 116.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 23\u201324 ====\nOn March 23, Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer [[Jeffrey DeWitt]] announced that the 2019 tax filing deadlines would be pushed to July 15, instead of the upcoming April 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer DeWitt Announce 2019 Tax Filings and Payment Deadline Extended to July 15, 2020 |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215938/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mayor also urged D.C. residents to remain at home except for \"essential activities,\" clarifying that she would not be issuing a [[shelter-in-place order]] as of now.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Katz |first1=Jeffrey |last2=Austermuhle |first2=Martin |last3=Pascale |first3=Jordan |last4=Chamberlin |first4=Victoria |title=UPDATED: D.C.-Area Residents Are Being Asked To Stay In Their Homes If They Can. How Is That Going To Work? |url=https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=WAMU |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323234638/https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn that day, Mayor Bowser also commissioned [[Republic Restoratives Distillery]] and [[Compass Coffee]], two locally owned companies, for the production of {{convert|2000|gal}} of [[hand sanitizer]] ({{convert|1000|gal}} each) for use by D.C. government workers and emergency responders.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242193836014796806|user=MayorBowser|title=1/ DC Government has commissioned 2,000 gallons of hand sanitizer from @RepublicRestore and @CompassCoffeeDC (1,000 each) as part of our response to the coronavirus (COVID-19).|date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 7:00 PM that day, the number of cases was 137.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 25 ====\nOn March 25, the third death in Washington, D.C. was a 75-year-old female with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242969615283740673|user=mayorbowser|date=25 March 2020|title=There's a third death in DC due to coronavirus (COVID-19). The patient, a 75-year-old female, was admitted to a hospital with underlying health conditions and passed away on March 25. She tested positive for COVID-19 and was included among the District\u2019s reporting data.}}</ref>\n\n==== March 30 ====\nOn March 30, Mayor Bowser announced a [[stay-at-home order]] that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to \nengage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-issues-stay-home-order|title=Mayor Bowser Issues Stay-At-Home Order|work=News Release|date=March 30, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-054%20Stay%20at%20Home.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-054: Stay At Home Order|work=Administrative Issuance System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAnyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison. Bowser said, \"Staying at home is the best way to flatten the curve and protect yourself, your family, and our entire community from COVID-19.\"<ref name=Franklin>{{cite news |last1=Franklin |first1=Jonathan |title=DC issues Stay-At-Home order: Here's what you can leave your house for |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dc-stay-at-home-order-why-and-what-you-can-leave-your-house-for/65-7f0f0bf1-1cb6-4921-a4a5-bbf7ddbaa88b |work=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA9]]|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the same day, [[Maryland]]'s Governor [[Larry Hogan]] and [[Virginia]]'s Governor [[Ralph Northam]] issued similar stay-at-home orders (see [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia|in Virginia]]). However, the penalties for violating those orders were different from those in the District.<ref name=\"Post March 30\">{{cite web|first1=Antonio|last=Olivo|first2=Ovetta|last2=Wiggins|first3=Gregory S.|last3=Schneider|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/hogan-northam-coronavirus-stay-home-orders/2020/03/30/5f36e146-722f-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|title=Hogan, Northam, Bowser order residents in Maryland, Virginia, D.C. to stay at home|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\n\n==== April 6 ====\nMayor Bowser announced a governmentwide hiring and pay freeze to ensure the District's funds are conserved.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |last2=Moore |first2=Jack |last3=Constantino |first3=Abigail |title=Coronavirus update: As area cases top 8,000, DC to take more emergency action |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/04/coronavirus-update-dc-maryland-virginia-april-6/ |work=WTOP |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Projections==\nA number of organizations have produced models that project the trajectory of the coronavirus outbreak.<ref name=Wan>{{cite news|first1=William|last1=Wan|first2=Carolyn Y.|last2=Johnson|date=April 7, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/04/06/americas-most-influential-coronavirus-model-just-revised-its-estimates-downward-not-every-model-agrees/|title=America\u2019s most influential coronavirus model just revised its estimates downward. But not every model agrees.|work=Health|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407034032/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/04/06/americas-most-influential-coronavirus-model-just-revised-its-estimates-downward-not-every-model-agrees/|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]] at the [[University of Washington]] in [[Seattle]] has constructed one of these (the IHME).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|title=Forecasting COVID-19 impact on hospital bed-days, ICU-days, ventilator days and deaths by US state in the next 4 months|date=April 7, 2020|location=[[Seattle, Washington]]|publisher=[[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407002253/http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Penn Medicine, a [[consortium]] of the [[Perelman School of Medicine]] and the [[University of Pennsylvania Health System]] in [[Philadelphia]], has constructed another, the COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME).<ref>(1) {{cite web|first=Mackenzie|last=Bean|date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/patient-flow/penn-medicine-shares-tool-for-covid-19-capacity-planning.html|title=Penn Medicine shares tool for COVID-19 capacity planning|work=Becker's Hospital Review|publisher=Becker's Healthcare|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=https://penn-chime.phl.io|title=COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME)|year=2020|location=[[Philadelphia]]|publisher=The Trustees of the [[University of Pennsylvania]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406135147/https://penn-chime.phl.io/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nAmong other things, the two models differ in the methods by which they calculate the effectiveness of [[social distancing]] in reducing the number of new COVID-19 infections.<ref name=Nirappil>{{cite news|first=Fenit|last=Nirappil|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|title=Coronavirus peak in D.C., Maryland, Virginia: FAQ on why models differ|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407055223/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The District is using the IHME as a best-case scenario and the more conservative CHIME to prepare for a surge that its planners consider to be more likely.<ref name=Wan/>\n\nAs of April 3, the CHIME was projecting that the peak hospital impact of the COVID-19 outbreak would occur in the District at the end of June.<ref name=Nirappil/> On April 5, an update to the IMHE revised that model's forecasts.<ref name=Wan/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthdata.org/news-release/new-ihme-covid-19-forecasts-find-lower-hospital-bed-need-epidemics-starting-peak|title=New IHME COVID-19 forecasts find lower hospital bed need, epidemics starting to peak confirms social distancing works|date=April 5, 2020|location=[[Seattle, Washington]]|publisher=[[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407234423/http://www.healthdata.org/news-release/new-ihme-covid-19-forecasts-find-lower-hospital-bed-need-epidemics-starting-peak|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>  The revised model suggests that the District will experience the peak of its outbreak on April 16.<ref name=Wan/>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 11, Mayor Muriel Bowser declared a state of emergency for the District of Columbia. The declaration allowed Bowser to request federal disaster funds and to address price gouging. The order also gave her additional authorities, including the ordering of quarantines without court approval.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Mayor Bowser Declares Public Health Emergency|work=News Release|date=March 11, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331050450/https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|title=DC mayor declares state of emergency due to coronavirus|first1=Jamiel|last1=Lynch|first2=Paul|last2=LeBlanc|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311230011/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487112-washington-dc-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus|title=Washington, DC, declares state of emergency over coronavirus|last=Moreno|first=J. Edward|date=2020-03-11|website=TheHill|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-12}}<br>(4) {{cite news|first1=Jenna|last1=Portnoy|first2=Fenit|last2=Nirappil|first3=Darran|last3=Simon|date=March 12, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|title=D.C. declares state of emergency as concerts, parades, church services are canceled|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327105804/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(5) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-045: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201523/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(6) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-046: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201521/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) shut down schools from March 16 to March 31. March 16 was reserved for professional development for teachers in preparation for the implementation of [[distance learning]]. The April Spring Break period was moved to March 17 to March 23, after which classes were set to resume online. DCPS-sponsored out-of-state travel for students was suspended until May 1 and staff travel was restricted. During the closure, several schools were set to offer meals to students from 10 am to 2 pm on weekdays.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Updates |url=https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |website=District of Columbia Public Schools |publisher=DC.Gov |accessdate=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313221000/https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the District government suspended on-site bar and restaurant service and shut down movie theaters and gyms. Restaurants could still offer food for carryout and delivery, but customers could not dine in.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |title=Second Va. man dies, D.C., Maryland restaurants, bars close as toll passes 100 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316234751/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |archive-date=2020-03-16 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser issued an order that prohibited mass gatherings of 50 or more people. The order also prohibited table service and service to standing customers at restaurants, bars and multi-purpose facilities, including seated, fast food and fast casual restaurants. Those businesses could only operate for take-out, \"grab-and-go\" and delivery operations.<ref name=\"March 20 order\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor\u2019s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|title=Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=News Release|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330150520/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor%E2%80%99s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-051: Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330201113/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe Mayor's March 20 order also required nightclubs, health clubs, health spas, massage parlors and theaters to continue their suspension of operations, which the District's government had initially ordered on March 17. The order further closed to the public all facilities that the District's Department of Recreation operated, including playgrounds, parks and athletic fields.<ref name=\"March 20 order\"/>\n\nThe District of Columbia Medical Reserve Corps (DC MRC), a volunteer organization under the [[District of Columbia Department of Health]], was mobilized to aid emergency workers in responding to the coronavirus pandemic throughout D.C. On March 21, Mayor Bowser called for more volunteers to join the task force.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser Encourages Volunteers to Join the DC Medical Reserve Corps |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215101/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Mayor Bowser issued an order \"to temporarily cease all non-essential business activities, including tour guides and touring services; gyms, health clubs, spas, and massage establishments; theaters, auditoriums, and other places of large gatherings; nightclubs; hair, nail, and tanning salons and barbershops; tattoo parlors; sales not involved in essential services; retail clothing stores; and professional services not devoted to assisting essential business operations.\"<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|title=New Mayor\u2019s Order Requires Temporary Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibits Gatherings of Ten or More People|work=News Release|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330200918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}} <br>(2) {{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Sophia|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|title=DC Closes Nonessential Businesses, DMV Centers to Stop Coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020|work=Coronavirus|publisher=[[WRC-TV|NBC4 Washington]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327133947/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBowser's March 24 order defined \"Construction and Building Trades\" as \"essential businesses\", but did not define private construction projects themselves as being \"essential\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, [[The Washington Post]] reported on March 28 that the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia had designated construction as \"essential,\" along with hospitals, grocery stores, banks and several other types of businesses. The ''Post'' reported that each of these jurisdictions had allowed private construction, including home building and commercial developments, to continue.<ref name=Lazo>{{cite news|first1=Luz|last1=Lazo|first2=Katherine|last2=Shaver|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|title=Work on region\u2019s big projects continues amid coronavirus, with construction an \u2018essential\u2019 business|work=Transportation|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401022830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nThe ''Post'' reported that John Falcicchio, Bowser's chief of staff, had stated that the District, Maryland and Virginia had agreed to follow the federal guidance declaring construction to be essential work. However, the ''Post'' reported that several states, including Pennsylvania and Vermont, had suspended or prohibited all construction work (except for emergencies) as unnecessary during a public health crisis. The Post further reported that the State of Washington's transportation department had suspended work on nearly all of its projects and that Washington's governor had clarified his [[Stay-at-home order|stay-at-home]] order to state that commercial and residential construction were generally prohibited \"because construction is not considered to be an essential activity.\"<ref name=Lazo/>\n\nThe [[United States Department of Homeland Security]]'s March 28 guidance on essential critical infrastructure lists as \"essential\" the construction of residential/shelter facilities and services (see \"[[essential services]]\"), energy-related facilities, communications and information technology, public works including the  construction of critical or strategic infrastructure and infrastructure that is temporarily required to support COVID-19 response, is for certain other types of community- or government-based operations, or is otherwise critical, strategic, or essential. The guidance does not contain any such listings for other types of construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|title=Guidance on the Essential Critical Infrastructure Workforce: Ensuring Community and National Resilience in COVID-19 Response|date=March 28, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[United States Department of Homeland Security]]: [[Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency]]: Office of the Director|accessdate=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402033910/https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Bowser announced a stay-at-home order that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to engage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\"/><ref name=\"Post March 30\"/> Anyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison.<ref name=Franklin/>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe pandemic affected several sports in the district. On March 12, [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]], and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317025811/https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Wizards season|Washington Wizards]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313004850/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Capitals season|Washington Capitals]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314025848/https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |date=2020-03-14 }} NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities districtwide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312213051/http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |date=2020-03-12 }} NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182102/https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |date=2020-03-18 }} MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] \u2013 for impact on Maryland counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia]] \u2013 for impact on Virginia counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://coronavirus.dc.gov/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Government of the District of Columbia]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2020 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Washington, D.C., United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.\n| width           = \n| image           = National Gallery of Art (49656625722).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Visitors wearing masks in the [[National Gallery of Art]], the day before it closed as a precaution against COVID-19\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| first_case      = March 7, 2020\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 902\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| deaths          = 21\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.dc.gov/}}\n}}\n\nThe first cases of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[Washington, D.C.]] were reported on March 7, 2020. {{As of|2020|04|02|df=US}}, there are 902 confirmed cases and 21 deaths in Washington, D.C. alone, with other cases in the surrounding counties of the [[Washington metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"dcgovdata\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Data |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |website=DC.Gov |publisher=Government of the District of Columbia |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134324/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Washington, D.C. medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February ===\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] signed an executive order that began to prepare Washington D.C. for coronavirus impacts on February 28. It was announced in the executive order that the District's Emergency Operations Center (EOC) would be activated on March 2, 2020 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to begin to \"coordinate inter-agency information sharing and identify logistical needs for critical incident responses.\" It was also announced that the Washington D.C. Department of Health and the Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency would be responsible for the response planning for COVID-19.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|title=Mayor's Order: District Government Preparations for the Coronavirus {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329193351/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n\n==== March 1\u20134 ====\nOn March 2 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m., the D.C. Emergency Operations Center was activated at an Enhanced Watch status, as per the executive order signed on February 28.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 3, Mayor Bowser, the D.C. Department of Health, and the D.C. Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency held a public briefing on the coronavirus and the District's \"monitoring, preparation, and response\" to it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|title=Mayor Bowser to Hold Briefing on the District's Coronavirus Monitoring, Preparation, and Response {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004155/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 5\u20137====\nOn March 7, the first two cases of COVID-19 in Washington, D.C. were confirmed. The first case was a [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] at [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]] who had not traveled outside the United States recently or had contact with another infected coronavirus patient. He participated in church services on February 23 and March 1. The rector felt better initially, but his condition deteriorated to the point of hospitalization, when it was confirmed he had coronavirus. After it was confirmed the rector contracted the virus, the church cancelled services indefinitely. The second case was a [[Nigeria]]n national who traveled to D.C. and went to a hospital in [[Maryland]] for treatment. Although the second man was being treated at a Maryland hospital, he was counted as the District's second case by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Georgetown Church Rector, Traveler Diagnosed as DC's First 2 Coronavirus Cases |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=NBC4 Washington |date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154326/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1236422174958895104|title=Late this afternoon, testing at the Public Health Lab at the DC Department of Forensic Sciences yielded its first presumptive positive coronavirus (COVID-19) case. Join me live at 7:30 p.m. for a briefing at the John A. Wilson Building.|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 8\u201310====\nOn March 9, [[School Without Walls (Washington, D.C.)|School Without Walls]], a public school in [[Foggy Bottom]], was closed by [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) for a full-day deep cleaning and disinfecting by a third-party contractor after an employee was exposed to COVID-19 the week before. The employee tested negative and entered a two-week quarantine. DCPS chancellor Lewis Ferebee announced the closing over Twitter the previous day.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1236819215920832513|date=8 Mar 2020|title=Tomorrow - 3/9 - School Without Walls High School will be closed. DCPS is conducting a deep cleaning and disinfecting of the building following an employee being exposed to COVID-19. Test results were negative, and there is no immediate risk to students and staff. cc: @SWWHSA}}</ref>\n\nThree more coronavirus cases in D.C. were confirmed the night of March 9, including an attendee of Christ Church Georgetown. D.C. officials recommended a two-week self-quarantine per CDC guidelines for anyone who attended Christ Church on February 24 or between February 28 and March 3. At that time, $1.5 million had been allocated to the pandemic response by the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gelman |first1=Scott |last2=Alvarez |first2=Alejandro |title=16 coronavirus cases confirmed in DC, Md. and Va. |url=https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=WTOP |date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313023822/https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[George Washington University]] announced classes will be moved online after spring break, starting on March 23 and continuing until at least April 5. In addition, all residential students were expected to no longer be living on campus beginning March 21. It was stated that an opening date would not be announced until the end of the instructional continuity period when a decision for the rest of the semester would be made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|title=George Washington University moving to online classes after spring break|date=2020-03-10|website=Fox 5 DC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311103004/https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Resource Center|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312130006/https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso on March 10, [[Georgetown Day School]], a private school, closed indefinitely and began a deep clean citing concerns about community members affiliated with [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volou |first1=Khalida |title=DC school closed due to coronavirus exposure linked to Christ Church Georgetown |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |agency=WUSA9 |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311195837/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 11\u201314====\nOn March 11, [[Maria Cantwell]], a U.S. senator from Washington state, closed her D.C. office due to one of her aides testing positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|title=Aide to Maria Cantwell tests positive for coronavirus. Senator closes her D.C. office|last=Lightman|first=David|website=thenewstribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313030257/https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|archive-date=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Georgetown University]] announced that it would be moving to virtual learning entirely beginning on March 16, and while campus would remain open and key services would remain accessible the university strongly suggested that students return to their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khan |first1=Saliqa |title=Georgetown University moves to virtual learning amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |work=WUSA9 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318192012/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the [[United States Capitol]], the [[White House]], and the [[United States Supreme Court Building]] closed to most of the public until April after several offices closed and multiple lawmakers went into precautionary quarantines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zengerle |first1=Patricia |last2=Heavey |first2=Susan |title=UPDATE 5-U.S. federal buildings put away the welcome mat as coronavirus hits |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-capitol/update-5-us-federal-buildings-put-away-the-welcome-mat-as-coronavirus-hits-idUSL1N2B50S4 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools|DCPS]] announced that they will cancel classes until April 1, implementing online distance learning.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1238430012417748993|date=13 March 2020|title=DCPS will modify operations from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31 to help limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. For more info about the closure schedule, meal locations for students & distance learning details, please visit: https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus}}</ref> Also on March 13, the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] (WMATA) escalated its operations to level 3 of its pandemic flu plan, announcing that service on the [[Washington Metro]] would be reduced to one train every 12 minutes from Monday to Saturday and one train every 15 minutes on Sunday beginning on March 17. In addition, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] service would change to a Saturday supplemental schedule on weekdays beginning on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|title=Metro takes additional steps, coordinates with public health authorities on COVID-19 {{!}} WMATA|website=wmata.com|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314155101/https://wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|archive-date=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|title=Metro to reduce transit service in response to the coronavirus outbreak|last=George|first=Justin|date=13 March 2020|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134151/https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|archive-date=14 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] held a press conference, announcing that gatherings of people over 60 years of age or with preexisting health issues would be limited to 10 people. The restriction would not apply to residences, schools, or places of work. For populations not at-risk the government promoted [[social distancing]] measures to limit the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vitka |first1=Will |last2=Bonk |first2=Valerie |title=Trump declares national emergency; DC bans mass gatherings |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |work=WTOP |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314183154/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, Mayor Bowser issued a statement confirming 6 more positive cases in Washington, D.C., bringing the total number of cases up to 16.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 14 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316100728/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|archive-date=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 15\u201316====\nOn March 15, Bowser's office announced one more positive case in Washington D.C., bringing the total cumulative number of cases to 17. The patient in this case is a 38-year-old woman who came into contact with another case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 15|work=Government of the District of Columbia|accessdate=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324170918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Hill Restaurant Group (HRG) said on March 16 they would comply would restrictions on bars and restaurants ordered by Mayor Bowser on March 15. Tom Johnson, the managing director of the group, had earlier said he would ignore the order, saying it would force his company into bankruptcy.<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487826-dc-restaurant-group-says-it-will-comply-with-restrictions-after-mayor DC restaurant group says it will comply with restrictions after mayor's warning] The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn the evening of March 16, Mayor Bowser's office released an update that confirmed five more positive cases of coronavirus in the District. The patients involved were a 23-year-old man, a 42-year-old woman with a history of travel to Europe, a 54-year-old woman, a 54-year-old man, and a 56-year-old man. These five cases brought the cumulative number of cases in D.C. to 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 16 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317204518/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|archive-date=2020-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 17\u201318 ====\nLate on March 17, Mayor Bowser's office announced the confirmation of nine more positive cases in the District, bringing the total number of positive cases to 31. The patients were all male and between the ages of 23 and 61. The 23-year-old patient was confirmed to have attended the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[National Harbor, Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 17 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319072119/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|archive-date=2020-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, at least 8 more cases were found, including a [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department|DC FEMS]] employee (leading to a quarantine of 73 firefighters), a [[U.S. marshal]] at the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia]], and an undergraduate student at the George Washington University who lives off-campus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jack |title=Coronavirus: Jump in new cases around region; DC first responder, US Marshal test positive |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |work=WTOP |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002447/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia]] announced new [[social distancing]] precautions in dealing with callers reporting flu-like symptoms as well as changes to police protocol for citations and warning notices in light of the restriction of certain services in the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Metropolitan Police Department Operational Adjustments During COVID-19 |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002500/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== March 19\u201320 ====\nAs of March 19, the number of confirmed cases sharply jumped to 71 as the supply of tests was expanded, an increase of 32 over one day.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1240791217647976448|user=MayorBowser|title=As of 8:00 p.m. on Thursday, March 19, the District\u2019s coronavirus (COVID-19) data includes 32 new positive cases, bringing the District\u2019s overall positive case total to 71 individuals. For more information visit:|date=19 March 2020}}</ref> This includes two more DC FEMS members and an eight-year-old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |title=Coronavirus: As more tests become available, DC sees jump in coronavirus cases |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014753/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Washington Metro]] closed the [[Smithsonian station|Smithsonian]] and [[Arlington Cemetery station|Arlington Cemetery]] stations until further notice. Metro ridership reduced by 85% due to the pandemic, leading to general manager Paul Wiedefeld submitting a request to Congress for emergency funding.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Augenstein |first1=Neal |title=Coronavirus: Metro asks Congress for emergency funding after ridership drops 85% |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014754/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser announced the first death related to COVID-19 in the District, a 59-year-old male, Deacon Brother John-Sebastian Laird-Hammond, [[Order of Friars Minor|OFM]], a [[Franciscan]] [[friar]] and [[permanent deacon]], a native of [[Minonk, Illinois]], with underlying medical conditions, specifically a multi-year battle with a type of [[leukemia]] who had been undergoing cancer treatments and was therefore more vulnerable to the virus.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | title=A Franciscan friar and deacon is DC's first known coronavirus fatality | access-date=2020-03-26 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329041046/https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | archive-date=2020-03-29 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Bowser tweet first death\">{{cite tweet|last=Bowser |first=Muriel |author-link=Muriel Bowser |user=MayorBowser |number=1241051533631946752 |date=2020-03-20 |title=It is with great sadness that we announce a tragic death and, on behalf of our residents, I share our love and condolences with the patient\u2019s family and friends. |access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The number of cases rose to 77.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nDCPS extended the school shutdown to April 24, meaning classes would be scheduled to resume on Monday, April 27. In preparation for the beginning of distance learning on March 24, the DCPS Distance Learning platform was released, publicly accessible at {{URL|https://dcps.instructure.com/courses/179580}}. Certain schools would continue to provide lunch on weekdays.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1241081893656956931|title=\ud83d\udea8UPDATE\ud83d\udea8 DCPS will be closed to all staff and students through Friday, April 24 to help mitigate the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. Classes will resume for all students on Monday, April 27. For more info please visit: http://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus.|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21\u201322 ====\n\nOn March 21, the D.C. government, operating through the Metropolitan Police Department and the [[National Park Service]] announced several road closures around beginning on March 22, 7:00 AM to 8:00 PM, in an effort to reduce congregation of tourists around monuments during the [[National Cherry Blossom Festival]]. These crowds had not been conforming to social distancing guidelines and thus presented a possible vector for the transmission of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Corse |first1=Alexa |title=Washington, D.C., Closes Streets to Prevent Coronavirus Transmission |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213549/https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TRAFFIC ADVISORY: Street Closures |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213607/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[District of Columbia Department of Parks and Recreation|DC Department of Parks and Recreation]] closed all of its facilities including parks, playgrounds, and athletic fields. Only dog parks remained open.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1241457230349811712|user=DCDPR|title=!!ALERT - All DPR facilities including Playgrounds + Gated Parks and Athletic Fields are CLOSED. Dog parks remain open. Stay informed http://coronavirus.dc.gov.|date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] announced reduced operation from 325 routes to only 20 high-use corridors. Real-time bus data would no longer be available and drivers may bypass stops in order to observe social distancing guidelines on buses. [[WMATA]] said it hoped to restore some routes with limited operation hours soon.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delaney |first1=Matthew |title=Coronavirus: 2nd death in DC; cases surge throughout region with more testing |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |work=WTOP |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235143/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:30 PM that day was 98.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nOn March 22, the second death due to COVID-19 was reported in the District, a 65-year-old woman with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1241783602830020615|title=1/ I am saddened to announce a second death related to COVID-19 in our community. The hearts and prayers of our entire city are with her family and loved ones.|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:00 PM that day was 116.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 23\u201324 ====\nOn March 23, Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer [[Jeffrey DeWitt]] announced that the 2019 tax filing deadlines would be pushed to July 15, instead of the upcoming April 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer DeWitt Announce 2019 Tax Filings and Payment Deadline Extended to July 15, 2020 |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215938/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mayor also urged D.C. residents to remain at home except for \"essential activities,\" clarifying that she would not be issuing a [[shelter-in-place order]] as of now.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Katz |first1=Jeffrey |last2=Austermuhle |first2=Martin |last3=Pascale |first3=Jordan |last4=Chamberlin |first4=Victoria |title=UPDATED: D.C.-Area Residents Are Being Asked To Stay In Their Homes If They Can. How Is That Going To Work? |url=https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=WAMU |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323234638/https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn that day, Mayor Bowser also commissioned [[Republic Restoratives Distillery]] and [[Compass Coffee]], two locally owned companies, for the production of {{convert|2000|gal}} of [[hand sanitizer]] ({{convert|1000|gal}} each) for use by D.C. government workers and emergency responders.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242193836014796806|user=MayorBowser|title=1/ DC Government has commissioned 2,000 gallons of hand sanitizer from @RepublicRestore and @CompassCoffeeDC (1,000 each) as part of our response to the coronavirus (COVID-19).|date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 7:00 PM that day, the number of cases was 137.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 25 ====\nOn March 25, the third death in Washington, D.C. was a 75-year-old female with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242969615283740673|user=mayorbowser|date=25 March 2020|title=There's a third death in DC due to coronavirus (COVID-19). The patient, a 75-year-old female, was admitted to a hospital with underlying health conditions and passed away on March 25. She tested positive for COVID-19 and was included among the District\u2019s reporting data.}}</ref>\n\n==== March 30 ====\nOn March 30, Mayor Bowser announced a [[stay-at-home order]] that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to \nengage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-issues-stay-home-order|title=Mayor Bowser Issues Stay-At-Home Order|work=News Release|date=March 30, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-054%20Stay%20at%20Home.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-054: Stay At Home Order|work=Administrative Issuance System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAnyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison. Bowser said, \"Staying at home is the best way to flatten the curve and protect yourself, your family, and our entire community from COVID-19.\"<ref name=Franklin>{{cite news |last1=Franklin |first1=Jonathan |title=DC issues Stay-At-Home order: Here's what you can leave your house for |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dc-stay-at-home-order-why-and-what-you-can-leave-your-house-for/65-7f0f0bf1-1cb6-4921-a4a5-bbf7ddbaa88b |work=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA9]]|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the same day, [[Maryland]]'s Governor [[Larry Hogan]] and [[Virginia]]'s Governor [[Ralph Northam]] issued similar stay-at-home orders (see [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia|in Virginia]]). However, the penalties for violating those orders were different from those in the District.<ref name=\"Post March 30\">{{cite web|first1=Antonio|last=Olivo|first2=Ovetta|last2=Wiggins|first3=Gregory S.|last3=Schneider|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/hogan-northam-coronavirus-stay-home-orders/2020/03/30/5f36e146-722f-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|title=Hogan, Northam, Bowser order residents in Maryland, Virginia, D.C. to stay at home|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\n\n==== April 6 ====\nMayor Bowser announced a governmentwide hiring and pay freeze to ensure the District's funds are conserved.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |last2=Moore |first2=Jack |last3=Constantino |first3=Abigail |title=Coronavirus update: As area cases top 8,000, DC to take more emergency action |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/04/coronavirus-update-dc-maryland-virginia-april-6/ |work=WTOP |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Projections==\nA number of organizations have produced models that project the trajectory of the coronavirus outbreak.A number of organizations have produced models that project the trajectory of the coronavirus outbreak.<ref name=Wan>{{cite news|first1=William|last1=Wan|first2=Carolyn Y.|last2=Johnson|date=April 7, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/04/06/americas-most-influential-coronavirus-model-just-revised-its-estimates-downward-not-every-model-agrees/|title=America\u2019s most influential coronavirus model just revised its estimates downward. But not every model agrees.|work=Health|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407034032/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/04/06/americas-most-influential-coronavirus-model-just-revised-its-estimates-downward-not-every-model-agrees/|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The [[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]] at the [[University of Washington]] in [[Seattle]] has constructed one of these (the IHME).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|title=Forecasting COVID-19 impact on hospital bed-days, ICU-days, ventilator days and deaths by US state in the next 4 months|date=April 7, 2020|location=[[Seattle, Washington]]|publisher=[[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407002253/http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/forecasting-covid-19-impact-hospital-bed-days-icu-days-ventilator-days-and-deaths|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Penn Medicine, a [[consortium]] of the [[Perelman School of Medicine]] and the [[University of Pennsylvania Health System]] in [[Philadelphia]], has constructed another, the COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME).<ref>(1) {{cite web|first=Mackenzie|last=Bean|date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/patient-flow/penn-medicine-shares-tool-for-covid-19-capacity-planning.html|title=Penn Medicine shares tool for COVID-19 capacity planning|work=Becker's Hospital Review|publisher=Becker's Healthcare|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=https://penn-chime.phl.io|title=COVID-19 Hospital Impact Model for Epidemics (CHIME)|year=2020|location=[[Philadelphia]]|publisher=The Trustees of the [[University of Pennsylvania]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406135147/https://penn-chime.phl.io/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nAmong other things, the two models differ in the methods by which they calculate the effectiveness of [[social distancing]] in reducing the number of new COVID-19 infections.<ref name=Nirappil>{{cite news|first=Fenit|last=Nirappil|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|title=Coronavirus peak in D.C., Maryland, Virginia: FAQ on why models differ|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407055223/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-peak-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/04/03/0636bc6c-75cf-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|archive-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The District is using the IHME as a best-case scenario and the more conservative CHIME to prepare for a surge that its planners consider to be more likely.<ref name=Wan/>\n\nAs of April 3, the CHIME was projecting that the peak hospital impact of the COVID-19 outbreak would occur in the District at the end of June.<ref name=Nirappil/> On April 5, an update to the IMHE revised that model's forecasts.<ref name=Wan/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthdata.org/news-release/new-ihme-covid-19-forecasts-find-lower-hospital-bed-need-epidemics-starting-peak|title=New IHME COVID-19 forecasts find lower hospital bed need, epidemics starting to peak confirms social distancing works|date=April 5, 2020|location=[[Seattle, Washington]]|publisher=[[Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2020}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407234423/http://www.healthdata.org/news-release/new-ihme-covid-19-forecasts-find-lower-hospital-bed-need-epidemics-starting-peak|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>  The revised model suggests that the District will experience the peak of its outbreak on April 16.<ref name=Wan/>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 11, Mayor Muriel Bowser declared a state of emergency for the District of Columbia. The declaration allowed Bowser to request federal disaster funds and to address price gouging. The order also gave her additional authorities, including the ordering of quarantines without court approval.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Mayor Bowser Declares Public Health Emergency|work=News Release|date=March 11, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331050450/https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|title=DC mayor declares state of emergency due to coronavirus|first1=Jamiel|last1=Lynch|first2=Paul|last2=LeBlanc|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311230011/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487112-washington-dc-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus|title=Washington, DC, declares state of emergency over coronavirus|last=Moreno|first=J. Edward|date=2020-03-11|website=TheHill|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-12}}<br>(4) {{cite news|first1=Jenna|last1=Portnoy|first2=Fenit|last2=Nirappil|first3=Darran|last3=Simon|date=March 12, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|title=D.C. declares state of emergency as concerts, parades, church services are canceled|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327105804/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(5) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-045: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201523/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(6) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-046: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201521/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) shut down schools from March 16 to March 31. March 16 was reserved for professional development for teachers in preparation for the implementation of [[distance learning]]. The April Spring Break period was moved to March 17 to March 23, after which classes were set to resume online. DCPS-sponsored out-of-state travel for students was suspended until May 1 and staff travel was restricted. During the closure, several schools were set to offer meals to students from 10 am to 2 pm on weekdays.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Updates |url=https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |website=District of Columbia Public Schools |publisher=DC.Gov |accessdate=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313221000/https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the District government suspended on-site bar and restaurant service and shut down movie theaters and gyms. Restaurants could still offer food for carryout and delivery, but customers could not dine in.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |title=Second Va. man dies, D.C., Maryland restaurants, bars close as toll passes 100 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316234751/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |archive-date=2020-03-16 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser issued an order that prohibited mass gatherings of 50 or more people. The order also prohibited table service and service to standing customers at restaurants, bars and multi-purpose facilities, including seated, fast food and fast casual restaurants. Those businesses could only operate for take-out, \"grab-and-go\" and delivery operations.<ref name=\"March 20 order\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor\u2019s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|title=Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=News Release|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330150520/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor%E2%80%99s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-051: Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330201113/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe Mayor's March 20 order also required nightclubs, health clubs, health spas, massage parlors and theaters to continue their suspension of operations, which the District's government had initially ordered on March 17. The order further closed to the public all facilities that the District's Department of Recreation operated, including playgrounds, parks and athletic fields.<ref name=\"March 20 order\"/>\n\nThe District of Columbia Medical Reserve Corps (DC MRC), a volunteer organization under the [[District of Columbia Department of Health]], was mobilized to aid emergency workers in responding to the coronavirus pandemic throughout D.C. On March 21, Mayor Bowser called for more volunteers to join the task force.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser Encourages Volunteers to Join the DC Medical Reserve Corps |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215101/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Mayor Bowser issued an order \"to temporarily cease all non-essential business activities, including tour guides and touring services; gyms, health clubs, spas, and massage establishments; theaters, auditoriums, and other places of large gatherings; nightclubs; hair, nail, and tanning salons and barbershops; tattoo parlors; sales not involved in essential services; retail clothing stores; and professional services not devoted to assisting essential business operations.\"<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|title=New Mayor\u2019s Order Requires Temporary Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibits Gatherings of Ten or More People|work=News Release|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330200918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}} <br>(2) {{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Sophia|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|title=DC Closes Nonessential Businesses, DMV Centers to Stop Coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020|work=Coronavirus|publisher=[[WRC-TV|NBC4 Washington]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327133947/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBowser's March 24 order defined \"Construction and Building Trades\" as \"essential businesses\", but did not define private construction projects themselves as being \"essential\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, [[The Washington Post]] reported on March 28 that the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia had designated construction as \"essential,\" along with hospitals, grocery stores, banks and several other types of businesses. The ''Post'' reported that each of these jurisdictions had allowed private construction, including home building and commercial developments, to continue.<ref name=Lazo>{{cite news|first1=Luz|last1=Lazo|first2=Katherine|last2=Shaver|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|title=Work on region\u2019s big projects continues amid coronavirus, with construction an \u2018essential\u2019 business|work=Transportation|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401022830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nThe ''Post'' reported that John Falcicchio, Bowser's chief of staff, had stated that the District, Maryland and Virginia had agreed to follow the federal guidance declaring construction to be essential work. However, the ''Post'' reported that several states, including Pennsylvania and Vermont, had suspended or prohibited all construction work (except for emergencies) as unnecessary during a public health crisis. The Post further reported that the State of Washington's transportation department had suspended work on nearly all of its projects and that Washington's governor had clarified his [[Stay-at-home order|stay-at-home]] order to state that commercial and residential construction were generally prohibited \"because construction is not considered to be an essential activity.\"<ref name=Lazo/>\n\nThe [[United States Department of Homeland Security]]'s March 28 guidance on essential critical infrastructure lists as \"essential\" the construction of residential/shelter facilities and services (see \"[[essential services]]\"), energy-related facilities, communications and information technology, public works including the  construction of critical or strategic infrastructure and infrastructure that is temporarily required to support COVID-19 response, is for certain other types of community- or government-based operations, or is otherwise critical, strategic, or essential. The guidance does not contain any such listings for other types of construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|title=Guidance on the Essential Critical Infrastructure Workforce: Ensuring Community and National Resilience in COVID-19 Response|date=March 28, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[United States Department of Homeland Security]]: [[Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency]]: Office of the Director|accessdate=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402033910/https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Bowser announced a stay-at-home order that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to engage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\"/><ref name=\"Post March 30\"/> Anyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison.<ref name=Franklin/>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe pandemic affected several sports in the district. On March 12, [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]], and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317025811/https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Wizards season|Washington Wizards]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313004850/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Capitals season|Washington Capitals]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314025848/https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |date=2020-03-14 }} NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities districtwide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312213051/http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |date=2020-03-12 }} NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182102/https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |date=2020-03-18 }} MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] \u2013 for impact on Maryland counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia]] \u2013 for impact on Virginia counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://coronavirus.dc.gov/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Government of the District of Columbia]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2020 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "Corker1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProjections:editorial change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Washington,_D.C."}
{"title_page": "Linjiang Campaign", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict          = [[Linjiang, Jilin|Linjiang]] Campaign\n| partof            = [[Chinese Civil War]]\n| image             = [[File:dong bei gong jun.png|center|197px]]\n| caption           = Chinese Communist troops on top of snow-covered grounds\n| place             = [[Linjiang]], [[Northeast China]]\n| date              = December 17, 1946 \u2013 April 1, 1947\n| result            = [[Chinese Communist Party|Communist]] victory\n| combatant1        = [[File:Flag of the Republic of China Army.svg|60px|center|Flag of the National Revolutionary Army]] <br> <div style=\"text-align:center\">[[National Revolutionary Army]]</div>\n| combatant2        = [[File:People's Liberation Army Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|60px|center|PLA]]<br> <div style=\"text-align:center\">[[Chinese Red Army]]</div>\n| commander1        = [[File:Flag of the Republic of China Army.svg|22px|Flag of the National Revolutionary Army]] [[Du Yuming]]\n| commander2        = {{flagicon|China|army}} [[Lin Biao]]\n| strength1         = 19 [[Division (military)|Divisions]]\n| strength2         = 12 [[Division (military)|Divisions]]\n| casualties1       = 40,000\n| casualties2       = unknown|\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Chinese Civil War}}\n'''Linjiang Campaign''' ([[Chinese character|Chinese]]: \u4e34\u6c5f\u6218\u5f79), also called by the [[communist]]s as the '''Campaign of Going South of the [[Songhua River|River]] for Three time to Guard [[Linjiang, Jilin|Linjiang]] for Four Times''' (San Xia Jiang Nan, Si Bao Linjiang Zhanyi, \u4e09\u4e0b\u6c5f\u5357\u56db\u4fdd\u4e34\u6c5f\u6218\u5f79), was a series of four failed offensives launched by the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] in attempt to eliminate the [[communist]] base south of [[Songhua River]] during the [[Chinese Civil War]].\n\n==Prelude==\nThe [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] had lost three [[Division (military)|divisions]] to the enemy by October, 1946 in [[northeast China]], and the local [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] commander, [[Du Yuming]] adjusted the strategy by planning to eradicate the enemy in a gradual but firm manner, instead of attempting to eliminate the enemy rapidly by a decisive engagement, which the enemy had refused to do.  The heart of this new strategy called for the elimination of the enemy base south of [[Songhua River]], headquartered at [[Linjiang, Jilin|Linjiang]].  After the enemy had been eradicated in the south, then the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] would push northward across the [[Songhua River]] and eliminate the enemy there.\n\nIn response to the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] strategy, the [[communist]] commander of [[northeast China]], [[Lin Biao]], and his followers accurately concluded that the [[communist]] base south of the [[Songhua River]] must be maintained at all cost, because it served to distract enemy and if it were lost, then the enemy could then devote its entire asset to pressure the [[communist]]s north of the [[Songhua River]], and the [[communist]]s in [[northeast China]] would then be endangered, and possibly facing total elimination.  The [[communist]]s decided to concentrate three columns with a total of nine [[Division (military)|divisions]] to stop the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] offensives, along with the help of three independent [[Division (military)|divisions]].\n\n==Order of battle==\n[[Kuomintang|Nationalist]] [[order of battle]]\n*The [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]]\n**The Newly Organized 22nd [[Division (military)|Division]]\n**The Newly Organized 30th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The Newly Organized 6th Army\n*The 52nd Army\n**The 2nd [[Division (military)|Division]]\n**The 195th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 60th Army\n*The 91st [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 71st Army\n*The 21st [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 87th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 88th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 89th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 207th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 54th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 13th Army\n\n[[Communist]] [[order of battle]]\n*The 3rd Column\n*The 4th Column\n*The 6th Column\n*The 1st Independent [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 2nd Independent [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 3rd Independent [[Division (military)|Division]]\n\n==First stage==\nOn December 17, 1946, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] send out six [[Division (military)|divisions]], including the 2nd [[Division (military)|division]] and the 195th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 52nd Army, the 91st [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 71st Army and one [[Division (military)|Division]] from each of the [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]], the Newly Organized 6th Army and the 60th Army to launch the first offensive against the [[communist]] base south of [[Songhua River]], and two more [[Division (military)|Divisions]] were deployed as reserves.  The initial [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] objective was to linkup [[Tonghua]] with Ji'an (\u96c6\u5b89) so that the enemy could be further squeezed into the mountain.  In response, on December 18, 1946, the [[communist]] 4th Column struck the regions between [[Fushun]], [[Huanren (town)|Huanren]] and [[Benxi]] behind the enemy line, and after more than a dozen days of fighting, succeeded in taking over more than twenty positions from the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]], including the critical ones at Alkaline Factory (Jian Chang, \u78b1\u5382) and Master Field (Tian Shifu, \u7530\u5e08\u4ed8), and killing more than 3,000 [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] troops in the process.  The [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 91st [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 71st Army was forced to withdraw to reinforce the rear, and this weakened the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] thrust by exposing the two [[Division (military)|divisions]] of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 52nd Army, which were ultimately badly mauled by the enemy who seized the opportunity and attacked with great efficiency and speed, resulting in the regions south of [[Tonghua]] newly taken by the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] earlier in the initial stage of the offensive falling back into the enemy hands.\n\nIn the north, the [[communist]]s massed three columns and three independent [[Division (military)|divisions]] to cross the [[Songhua River]] on January 5, 1947, to besiege the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] strategic location of Pagoda Wood (Tamu, \u5854\u6728), forced the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] offensive into a complete halt and then redeploying two attacking [[Division (military)|divisions]] to reinforce Pagoda Wood (Tamu, \u5854\u6728).  However, when the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] reinforcement reached the region between Zhangmazi Ditch (Zhangmazi Gou, \u5f20\u9ebb\u5b50\u6c9f) and the Jiao Family's Ridge (Jiajia Ling,\u7126\u5bb6\u5cad), they learned that Pagoda Wood (Tamu, \u5854\u6728) had already fallen into the enemy hands, with the entire garrison consisted of a security force regiment and two regiments of the [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]] being completely annihilated by the enemy.  The enemy consequently returned to north of the [[Songhua River]] on January 19, 1947.\n\nAchieving their objectives when the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] stopped their assault on [[Linjiang, Jilin|Linjiang]], the [[communist]]s withdrew to their original bases and the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] could not pursuit the enemy anymore due to the sudden change of the weather when the temperature suddenly dropped to forty degrees below zero.\n\n==Second stage==\nThe [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] correctly assessed that they must avoid fighting at the two fronts and thus attacks on the [[communist]] base in the south must continue in order to eliminate the enemy.  On January 30, 1947, a second offensive was launched with four [[Division (military)|divisions]]: the 21st [[Division (military)|Division]], the 2nd [[Division (military)|Division]] and the 195th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 52nd Army, and the 207th [[Division (military)|Division]].  The [[communist]]s in turn, deployed the 3rd Column and the 10th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 4th Column to stop the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] offensive and on February 5, 1947, the weakest [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] [[Division (military)|division]], the 195th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 52nd Army was ambushed at Gaolichengzi (\u9ad8\u529b\u57ce\u5b50), suffering more than 2,000 fatalities.  On February 6, 1947, a regiment of the advance guard of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 207th [[Division (military)|Division]] was annihilated at Sanyuanpu (\u4e09\u6e90\u6d66) by dusk, and after the setback, the commander of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 207th [[Division (military)|Division]] wisely chose to stop and withdraw.\n\nMeanwhile, the [[communist]] 4th Column once again struck the regions between [[Fushun]] (\u629a\u987a), [[Huanren (town)|Huanren]] (\u6853\u4ec1) and [[Benxi]] (\u672c\u6eaa) deep behind the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] line to take over numerous [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] strongholds, and when combined with [[communist]] victories elsewhere, eventually succeeding in forcing the second [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] offensive come to a complete stop again, and the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] were forced to give up the newly conquered lands when one [[Division (military)|division]] was redeployed to reinforce the rear and other begun their withdraw.\n\n==Third Stage==\nJust a week after the failure of the second offensive, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] launched their third offensive against the enemy by deploying the 2nd [[Division (military)|Division]] and the 195th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 52nd Army, the 91st [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 71st Army, the Newly Organized 22nd [[Division (military)|Division]] of the [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]] and the 21st [[Division (military)|Division]] to attack in four fronts on February 13, 1947.  A detachment of the [[communist]] 4th Column again played the same trick that was so successful in the previous two counteroffensives: struck the regions between [[Fushun]], [[Huanren (town)|Huanren]] and [[Benxi]] deep behind the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] line again and attracting three [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] [[Division (military)|divisions]] so that they could not be used to attack the [[communist]] base south of [[Songhua River]], while in the meantime, the  [[communist]] 3rd Column and the 4th Column first annihilated an entire regiment of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 21st [[Division (military)|Division]] at Tonggou (\u901a\u6c9f), and then annihilated another regiment of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 91st [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 71st Army at Daibeicha (\u5927\u5317\u5c94), forcing the two [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] [[Division (military)|Divisions]] to withdraw on February 22, 1947.  The newly gained territory/towns in the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] third offensive such as Huinan (\u8f89\u5357), Golden River (Jinchuan, \u91d1\u5ddd), Willow River (Liuhe, \u67f3\u6cb3) and Ji'an (\u96c6\u5b89) therefore fell back into the enemy hands.\n\nOn the other front, the [[communist]] force crossed the [[Songhua River]] on February 21, 1947, and attacked regions surrounding [[Changchun]] to distract the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]].  After annihilating an entire regiment of the Newly Organized 30th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]] at the town of Chengzi Street (Chengzi Jie, \u57ce\u5b50\u8857), the [[communist]] 6th Column turned north and linked up with the [[communist]] 2nd Independent [[Division (military)|Division]] to besiege [[Dehui]] (\u5fb7\u60e0) in order to draw [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] forces away from the [[communist]] base.  The plan succeeded and the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] redeployed [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]] (including its Newly Organized 22nd [[Division (military)|Division]]), the 87th [[Division (military)|Division]], and the 88th [[Division (military)|Division]] to reinforce their besieged comrades-in-arms.  The enemy force wisely chose to withdraw back to the north of [[Songhua River]] on March 2, 1947, before the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] reinforcement could reach [[Dehui]].\n\nThe [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] were determined not to let the enemy to get away so they continued their push northward, but in doing so, the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] were severely overstretched.  Seizing the opportunity, the enemy crossed the [[Songhua River]] again on March 8, 1947, for the third time to attack, and the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] commanders had no choice but to order a general retreat.  However, the retreating [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] force was caught up by the pursuing enemy and the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 88th [[Division (military)|Division]] was annihilated at the Village of the Mountain of Guo (Guo-shan Tun, \u90ed\u5c71\u5c6f), and the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 87th [[Division (military)|Division]] was badly mauled at the Village Next to the Mountain (Kao-shan Tun, \u9760\u5c71\u5c6f).  On March 12, 1947, [[Nong'an County|Nong'an]] (\u519c\u5b89) was besieged and the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] were forced to redeploy the [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]] (including its Newly Organized 22nd [[Division (military)|Division]]) and the 54th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 13th Army from [[Rehe (province)|Rehe]] (\u70ed\u6cb3) to reinforce their besieged comrades-in-arms again.  Succeeding in distracting the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] who had to stop their third offensives, the enemy withdrew to the north of [[Songhua River]].\n\n==Fourth Stage==\nNot wanting to admitting defeat, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] launched their fourth offensive against the [[communist]] base south of [[Songhua River]] on March 26, 1947, with a total strength of twenty regiments attacking in three fronts.  The enemy, in response, targeted the central front headed by the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 89th [[Division (military)|Division]], who was dangerously exposed because its push was much too fast.  While other enemy units resisted the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] left and right fronts, the main body of the enemy force ambushed the 89th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] central front on April 1, 1947, annihilating the entire [[Division (military)|Division]].  Learning the news of the annihilation of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 89th [[Division (military)|Division]], the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] on the other two fronts immediately withdrew.\n\nThe failure of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] fourth offensive marked the end of campaign because the units deployed were the same ones that participated in earlier offensives, and thus was gravely overworked and overstretched.  The [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] could not afford to expend anymore valuable troops and must reserve their strength to defend the territory currently under their control.\n\n==Outcome==\nThe [[Linjiang, Jilin|Linjiang]] Campaign marked the turning point of the battlefield of [[northeast China]]: after this [[communist]] victory, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] in [[northeast China]] were forced to be on the defensive, and could no longer to launch any offensives, while in contrast, the [[communist]]s would be on the offensives from then on.  It must be said, however, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] were still quite capable of knocking out the entire [[communist]] force in [[northeast China]] if the right tactics were applied, such as concentrating on annihilating enemy force instead of gaining and holding on to more land, as suggested by many local [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] commanders, but their correct suggestion was overridden by [[Chiang Kai-shek]] infatuation with conquering more land.  Furthermore, even if the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] were unable to annihilate the enemy at the time, they could still reserve their strength by giving up [[northeast China]] and saving troops, and the situation had improved, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] would be able to retake [[northeast China]], as suggested by [[Chen Cheng]] in 1946.  Again, this alternative would also contradicting with Chiang's uncompromising stand, which ultimately doomed the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Chinese battles#Modern China|List of Battles of Chinese Civil War]]\n*[[National Revolutionary Army]]\n*[[History of the People's Liberation Army]]\n*[[Chinese Civil War]]\n{{Chinese Civil War}}\n\n==References==\n{{no footnotes|date=September 2014}}\n*Zhu, Zongzhen and Wang, Chaoguang, ''Liberation War History'', 1st Edition, Social Scientific Literary Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 2000, {{ISBN|7-80149-207-2}} (set)\n*Zhang, Ping, ''History of the Liberation War'', 1st Edition, Chinese Youth Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 1987, {{ISBN|7-5006-0081-X}} (pbk.)\n*Jie, Lifu, ''Records of the Libration War: The Decisive Battle of Two Kinds of Fates'', 1st Edition, [[Hebei]] People's Publishing House in [[Shijiazhuang]], 1990, {{ISBN|7-202-00733-9}} (set)\n*Literary and Historical Research Committee of the [[Anhui]] Committee of the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]], ''Liberation War'', 1st Edition, [[Anhui]] People's Publishing House in [[Hefei]], 1987, {{ISBN|7-212-00007-8}}\n*Li, Zuomin, ''Heroic Division and Iron Horse: Records of the Liberation War'', 1st Edition, [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist]] Party History Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 2004, {{ISBN|7-80199-029-3}}\n*Wang, Xingsheng, and Zhang, Jingshan, ''Chinese Liberation War'', 1st Edition, [[People's Liberation Army]] Literature and Art Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 2001, {{ISBN|7-5033-1351-X}} (set)\n*Huang, Youlan, ''History of the Chinese People's Liberation War'', 1st Edition, Archives Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 1992, {{ISBN|7-80019-338-1}}\n*Liu Wusheng, ''From [[Yan'an]] to [[Beijing]]: A Collection of Military Records and Research Publications of Important Campaigns in the Liberation War'', 1st Edition, Central Literary Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 1993, {{ISBN|7-5073-0074-9}}\n*Tang, Yilu and Bi, Jianzhong, ''History of Chinese [[People's Liberation Army]] in Chinese Liberation War'', 1st Edition, Military Scientific Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 1993 &ndash; 1997, {{ISBN|7-80021-719-1}} (Volum 1), 7800219615 (Volum 2), 7800219631 (Volum 3), 7801370937 (Volum 4), and 7801370953 (Volum 5)\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1946]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1947]]\n[[Category:Campaigns of the Chinese Civil War]]\n[[Category:1946 in China]]\n[[Category:1947 in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=[[Linjiang, Jilin|Linjiang]] Campaign\n|partof=[[Chinese Civil War]]\n|image=[[File:dong bei gong jun.png|center|197px]]\n|caption=Chinese Communist troops on top of snow-covered grounds\n|place=[[Northeast China]]\n|date=December 17, 1946 \u2013 April 1, 1947\n|result=[[Chinese Communist Party|Communist]] victory\n|combatant1=[[File:Flag of the Republic of China Army.svg|60px|center|Flag of the National Revolutionary Army]] <br> <div style=\"text-align:center\">[[National Revolutionary Army]]</div>\n|combatant2=[[File:People's Liberation Army Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|60px|center|PLA]]<br> <div style=\"text-align:center\">[[Chinese Red Army]]</div>\n|commander1=[[File:Flag of the Republic of China Army.svg|22px|Flag of the National Revolutionary Army]] [[Du Yuming]]\n|commander2={{flagicon|China|army}} [[Lin Biao]]\n|strength1= 19 [[Division (military)|Divisions]]\n|strength2= 12 [[Division (military)|Divisions]]\n|casualties1= 40,000\n|casualties2= unknown\n|}}\n{{Campaignbox Chinese Civil War}}\n'''Linjiang Campaign''' ([[Chinese character|Chinese]]: \u4e34\u6c5f\u6218\u5f79), also called by the [[communist]]s as the '''Campaign of Going South of the [[Songhua River|River]] for Three time to Guard [[Linjiang, Jilin|Linjiang]] for Four Times''' (San Xia Jiang Nan, Si Bao Linjiang Zhanyi, \u4e09\u4e0b\u6c5f\u5357\u56db\u4fdd\u4e34\u6c5f\u6218\u5f79), was a series of four failed offensives launched by the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] in attempt to eliminate the [[communist]] base south of [[Songhua River]] during the [[Chinese Civil War]].\n\n==Prelude==\nThe [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] had lost three [[Division (military)|divisions]] to the enemy by October, 1946 in [[northeast China]], and the local [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] commander, [[Du Yuming]] adjusted the strategy by planning to eradicate the enemy in a gradual but firm manner, instead of attempting to eliminate the enemy rapidly by a decisive engagement, which the enemy had refused to do.  The heart of this new strategy called for the elimination of the enemy base south of [[Songhua River]], headquartered at [[Linjiang, Jilin|Linjiang]].  After the enemy had been eradicated in the south, then the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] would push northward across the [[Songhua River]] and eliminate the enemy there.\n\nIn response to the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] strategy, the [[communist]] commander of [[northeast China]], [[Lin Biao]], and his followers accurately concluded that the [[communist]] base south of the [[Songhua River]] must be maintained at all cost, because it served to distract enemy and if it were lost, then the enemy could then devote its entire asset to pressure the [[communist]]s north of the [[Songhua River]], and the [[communist]]s in [[northeast China]] would then be endangered, and possibly facing total elimination.  The [[communist]]s decided to concentrate three columns with a total of nine [[Division (military)|divisions]] to stop the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] offensives, along with the help of three independent [[Division (military)|divisions]].\n\n==Order of battle==\n[[Kuomintang|Nationalist]] [[order of battle]]\n*The [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]]\n**The Newly Organized 22nd [[Division (military)|Division]]\n**The Newly Organized 30th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The Newly Organized 6th Army\n*The 52nd Army\n**The 2nd [[Division (military)|Division]]\n**The 195th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 60th Army\n*The 91st [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 71st Army\n*The 21st [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 87th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 88th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 89th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 207th [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 54th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 13th Army\n\n[[Communist]] [[order of battle]]\n*The 3rd Column\n*The 4th Column\n*The 6th Column\n*The 1st Independent [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 2nd Independent [[Division (military)|Division]]\n*The 3rd Independent [[Division (military)|Division]]\n\n==First stage==\nOn December 17, 1946, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] send out six [[Division (military)|divisions]], including the 2nd [[Division (military)|division]] and the 195th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 52nd Army, the 91st [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 71st Army and one [[Division (military)|Division]] from each of the [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]], the Newly Organized 6th Army and the 60th Army to launch the first offensive against the [[communist]] base south of [[Songhua River]], and two more [[Division (military)|Divisions]] were deployed as reserves.  The initial [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] objective was to linkup [[Tonghua]] with Ji'an (\u96c6\u5b89) so that the enemy could be further squeezed into the mountain.  In response, on December 18, 1946, the [[communist]] 4th Column struck the regions between [[Fushun]], [[Huanren (town)|Huanren]] and [[Benxi]] behind the enemy line, and after more than a dozen days of fighting, succeeded in taking over more than twenty positions from the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]], including the critical ones at Alkaline Factory (Jian Chang, \u78b1\u5382) and Master Field (Tian Shifu, \u7530\u5e08\u4ed8), and killing more than 3,000 [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] troops in the process.  The [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 91st [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 71st Army was forced to withdraw to reinforce the rear, and this weakened the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] thrust by exposing the two [[Division (military)|divisions]] of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 52nd Army, which were ultimately badly mauled by the enemy who seized the opportunity and attacked with great efficiency and speed, resulting in the regions south of [[Tonghua]] newly taken by the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] earlier in the initial stage of the offensive falling back into the enemy hands.\n\nIn the north, the [[communist]]s massed three columns and three independent [[Division (military)|divisions]] to cross the [[Songhua River]] on January 5, 1947, to besiege the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] strategic location of Pagoda Wood (Tamu, \u5854\u6728), forced the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] offensive into a complete halt and then redeploying two attacking [[Division (military)|divisions]] to reinforce Pagoda Wood (Tamu, \u5854\u6728).  However, when the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] reinforcement reached the region between Zhangmazi Ditch (Zhangmazi Gou, \u5f20\u9ebb\u5b50\u6c9f) and the Jiao Family's Ridge (Jiajia Ling,\u7126\u5bb6\u5cad), they learned that Pagoda Wood (Tamu, \u5854\u6728) had already fallen into the enemy hands, with the entire garrison consisted of a security force regiment and two regiments of the [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]] being completely annihilated by the enemy.  The enemy consequently returned to north of the [[Songhua River]] on January 19, 1947.\n\nAchieving their objectives when the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] stopped their assault on [[Linjiang, Jilin|Linjiang]], the [[communist]]s withdrew to their original bases and the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] could not pursuit the enemy anymore due to the sudden change of the weather when the temperature suddenly dropped to forty degrees below zero.\n\n==Second stage==\nThe [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] correctly assessed that they must avoid fighting at the two fronts and thus attacks on the [[communist]] base in the south must continue in order to eliminate the enemy.  On January 30, 1947, a second offensive was launched with four [[Division (military)|divisions]]: the 21st [[Division (military)|Division]], the 2nd [[Division (military)|Division]] and the 195th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 52nd Army, and the 207th [[Division (military)|Division]].  The [[communist]]s in turn, deployed the 3rd Column and the 10th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 4th Column to stop the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] offensive and on February 5, 1947, the weakest [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] [[Division (military)|division]], the 195th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 52nd Army was ambushed at Gaolichengzi (\u9ad8\u529b\u57ce\u5b50), suffering more than 2,000 fatalities.  On February 6, 1947, a regiment of the advance guard of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 207th [[Division (military)|Division]] was annihilated at Sanyuanpu (\u4e09\u6e90\u6d66) by dusk, and after the setback, the commander of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 207th [[Division (military)|Division]] wisely chose to stop and withdraw.\n\nMeanwhile, the [[communist]] 4th Column once again struck the regions between [[Fushun]] (\u629a\u987a), [[Huanren (town)|Huanren]] (\u6853\u4ec1) and [[Benxi]] (\u672c\u6eaa) deep behind the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] line to take over numerous [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] strongholds, and when combined with [[communist]] victories elsewhere, eventually succeeding in forcing the second [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] offensive come to a complete stop again, and the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] were forced to give up the newly conquered lands when one [[Division (military)|division]] was redeployed to reinforce the rear and other begun their withdraw.\n\n==Third Stage==\nJust a week after the failure of the second offensive, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] launched their third offensive against the enemy by deploying the 2nd [[Division (military)|Division]] and the 195th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 52nd Army, the 91st [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 71st Army, the Newly Organized 22nd [[Division (military)|Division]] of the [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]] and the 21st [[Division (military)|Division]] to attack in four fronts on February 13, 1947.  A detachment of the [[communist]] 4th Column again played the same trick that was so successful in the previous two counteroffensives: struck the regions between [[Fushun]], [[Huanren (town)|Huanren]] and [[Benxi]] deep behind the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] line again and attracting three [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] [[Division (military)|divisions]] so that they could not be used to attack the [[communist]] base south of [[Songhua River]], while in the meantime, the  [[communist]] 3rd Column and the 4th Column first annihilated an entire regiment of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 21st [[Division (military)|Division]] at Tonggou (\u901a\u6c9f), and then annihilated another regiment of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 91st [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 71st Army at Daibeicha (\u5927\u5317\u5c94), forcing the two [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] [[Division (military)|Divisions]] to withdraw on February 22, 1947.  The newly gained territory/towns in the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] third offensive such as Huinan (\u8f89\u5357), Golden River (Jinchuan, \u91d1\u5ddd), Willow River (Liuhe, \u67f3\u6cb3) and Ji'an (\u96c6\u5b89) therefore fell back into the enemy hands.\n\nOn the other front, the [[communist]] force crossed the [[Songhua River]] on February 21, 1947, and attacked regions surrounding [[Changchun]] to distract the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]].  After annihilating an entire regiment of the Newly Organized 30th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]] at the town of Chengzi Street (Chengzi Jie, \u57ce\u5b50\u8857), the [[communist]] 6th Column turned north and linked up with the [[communist]] 2nd Independent [[Division (military)|Division]] to besiege [[Dehui]] (\u5fb7\u60e0) in order to draw [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] forces away from the [[communist]] base.  The plan succeeded and the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] redeployed [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]] (including its Newly Organized 22nd [[Division (military)|Division]]), the 87th [[Division (military)|Division]], and the 88th [[Division (military)|Division]] to reinforce their besieged comrades-in-arms.  The enemy force wisely chose to withdraw back to the north of [[Songhua River]] on March 2, 1947, before the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] reinforcement could reach [[Dehui]].\n\nThe [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] were determined not to let the enemy to get away so they continued their push northward, but in doing so, the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] were severely overstretched.  Seizing the opportunity, the enemy crossed the [[Songhua River]] again on March 8, 1947, for the third time to attack, and the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] commanders had no choice but to order a general retreat.  However, the retreating [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] force was caught up by the pursuing enemy and the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 88th [[Division (military)|Division]] was annihilated at the Village of the Mountain of Guo (Guo-shan Tun, \u90ed\u5c71\u5c6f), and the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 87th [[Division (military)|Division]] was badly mauled at the Village Next to the Mountain (Kao-shan Tun, \u9760\u5c71\u5c6f).  On March 12, 1947, [[Nong'an County|Nong'an]] (\u519c\u5b89) was besieged and the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] were forced to redeploy the [[New 1st Army|Newly Organized 1st Army]] (including its Newly Organized 22nd [[Division (military)|Division]]) and the 54th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the 13th Army from [[Rehe (province)|Rehe]] (\u70ed\u6cb3) to reinforce their besieged comrades-in-arms again.  Succeeding in distracting the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] who had to stop their third offensives, the enemy withdrew to the north of [[Songhua River]].\n\n==Fourth Stage==\nNot wanting to admitting defeat, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] launched their fourth offensive against the [[communist]] base south of [[Songhua River]] on March 26, 1947, with a total strength of twenty regiments attacking in three fronts.  The enemy, in response, targeted the central front headed by the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 89th [[Division (military)|Division]], who was dangerously exposed because its push was much too fast.  While other enemy units resisted the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] left and right fronts, the main body of the enemy force ambushed the 89th [[Division (military)|Division]] of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] central front on April 1, 1947, annihilating the entire [[Division (military)|Division]].  Learning the news of the annihilation of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] 89th [[Division (military)|Division]], the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] on the other two fronts immediately withdrew.\n\nThe failure of the [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] fourth offensive marked the end of campaign because the units deployed were the same ones that participated in earlier offensives, and thus was gravely overworked and overstretched.  The [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] could not afford to expend anymore valuable troops and must reserve their strength to defend the territory currently under their control.\n\n==Outcome==\nThe [[Linjiang, Jilin|Linjiang]] Campaign marked the turning point of the battlefield of [[northeast China]]: after this [[communist]] victory, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] in [[northeast China]] were forced to be on the defensive, and could no longer to launch any offensives, while in contrast, the [[communist]]s would be on the offensives from then on.  It must be said, however, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] were still quite capable of knocking out the entire [[communist]] force in [[northeast China]] if the right tactics were applied, such as concentrating on annihilating enemy force instead of gaining and holding on to more land, as suggested by many local [[Kuomintang|nationalist]] commanders, but their correct suggestion was overridden by [[Chiang Kai-shek]] infatuation with conquering more land.  Furthermore, even if the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] were unable to annihilate the enemy at the time, they could still reserve their strength by giving up [[northeast China]] and saving troops, and the situation had improved, the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]] would be able to retake [[northeast China]], as suggested by [[Chen Cheng]] in 1946.  Again, this alternative would also contradicting with Chiang's uncompromising stand, which ultimately doomed the [[Kuomintang|nationalists]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Chinese battles#Modern China|List of Battles of Chinese Civil War]]\n*[[National Revolutionary Army]]\n*[[History of the People's Liberation Army]]\n*[[Chinese Civil War]]\n{{Chinese Civil War}}\n\n==References==\n{{no footnotes|date=September 2014}}\n*Zhu, Zongzhen and Wang, Chaoguang, ''Liberation War History'', 1st Edition, Social Scientific Literary Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 2000, {{ISBN|7-80149-207-2}} (set)\n*Zhang, Ping, ''History of the Liberation War'', 1st Edition, Chinese Youth Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 1987, {{ISBN|7-5006-0081-X}} (pbk.)\n*Jie, Lifu, ''Records of the Libration War: The Decisive Battle of Two Kinds of Fates'', 1st Edition, [[Hebei]] People's Publishing House in [[Shijiazhuang]], 1990, {{ISBN|7-202-00733-9}} (set)\n*Literary and Historical Research Committee of the [[Anhui]] Committee of the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]], ''Liberation War'', 1st Edition, [[Anhui]] People's Publishing House in [[Hefei]], 1987, {{ISBN|7-212-00007-8}}\n*Li, Zuomin, ''Heroic Division and Iron Horse: Records of the Liberation War'', 1st Edition, [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist]] Party History Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 2004, {{ISBN|7-80199-029-3}}\n*Wang, Xingsheng, and Zhang, Jingshan, ''Chinese Liberation War'', 1st Edition, [[People's Liberation Army]] Literature and Art Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 2001, {{ISBN|7-5033-1351-X}} (set)\n*Huang, Youlan, ''History of the Chinese People's Liberation War'', 1st Edition, Archives Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 1992, {{ISBN|7-80019-338-1}}\n*Liu Wusheng, ''From [[Yan'an]] to [[Beijing]]: A Collection of Military Records and Research Publications of Important Campaigns in the Liberation War'', 1st Edition, Central Literary Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 1993, {{ISBN|7-5073-0074-9}}\n*Tang, Yilu and Bi, Jianzhong, ''History of Chinese [[People's Liberation Army]] in Chinese Liberation War'', 1st Edition, Military Scientific Publishing House in [[Beijing]], 1993 &ndash; 1997, {{ISBN|7-80021-719-1}} (Volum 1), 7800219615 (Volum 2), 7800219631 (Volum 3), 7801370937 (Volum 4), and 7801370953 (Volum 5)\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1946]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1947]]\n[[Category:Campaigns of the Chinese Civil War]]\n[[Category:1946 in China]]\n[[Category:1947 in China]]\n", "name_user": "Kevin9217", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linjiang_Campaign"}
{"title_page": "Mulayam Singh Yadav", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician and former chief minister of the state of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Use Indian English|date= October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image            = Mulayam Singh Yadav (28993165375).jpg\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|2020|11|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Saifai]], [[United Provinces (1937\u201350)|United Provinces]], [[British India]]\n| residence        = [[Saifai]], [[Etawah district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| office          = [[Samajwadi Party|Chairman of the Samajwadi Party]]\n| term_start      = 1992\n| term_end        = 2017\n| predecessor     = ''Position established''\n| successor       = [[Akhilesh Yadav]]\n| office1          = [[Member of Parliament]], [[Lok Sabha]]\n| constituency1 = [[Mainpuri (Lok Sabha constituency)|Mainpuri]]\n| term_start1 = 23 May 2019\n| predecessor1     = [[Tej Pratap Singh Yadav]]\n| constituency2    = [[Azamgarh (Lok Sabha constituency)|Azamgarh]]\n| term_start2      = 2014\n| term_end2        = 2019\n| predecessor2     = [[Ramakant Yadav (politician)|Ramakant Yadav]]\n| successor2       = [[Akhilesh Yadav]]\n| term_start3 = 2009\n| term_end3 = 2014\n| constituency3 = [[Mainpuri (Lok Sabha constituency)|Mainpuri]]\n| term_start4 = 2004\n| term_end4 = 2004 \n| constituency4 = [[Mainpuri (Lok Sabha constituency)|Mainpuri]]\n| term_start5 = 1998\n| term_end5 = 2004\n| predecessor5     = [[D. P. Yadav]] \n| successor5       = [[Ram Gopal Yadav]] \n| constituency5 = [[Sambhal (Lok Sabha constituency)|Sambhal]] \n|term_start6 = 1996\n|term_end6 = 1998\n| constituency6 = [[Mainpuri (Lok Sabha constituency)|Mainpuri]]\n| office7          = 15th [[Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh]]\n| term_start7      = 29 August 2003\n| term_end7       =13 May 2007\n| predecessor7     = [[Mayawati]]\n| successor7       = [[Mayawati]]\n| term_start8      = 5 December 1993\n| term_end8        = 3 June 1995\n| predecessor8     = [[President's Rule]]\n| successor8       = [[Mayawati]]\n| term_start9      = 5 December 1989\n| term_end9        = 24 June 1991\n| predecessor9     = [[Narayan Datt Tiwari]]\n| successor9       = [[Kalyan Singh]]\n| office10          = [[Minister of Defence (India)]]\n| primeminister10   = [[H. D. Deve Gowda]],\n                     [[I. K. Gujral]]\n| term_start10       = 1 June 1996\n| term_end10         = 19 March 1998\n| predecessor10       = [[Pramod Mahajan]]\n| successor10         = [[George Fernandes]]\n| office11 = [[Member of Legislative Assembly]], [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly|Uttar Pradesh]] \n| term_start11 = 1967\n| term_end11 = 1969\n| predecessor11     = Natthu Singh\n| successor11       = Bishambhar Singh Yadav\n| constituency11 = [[Jaswantnagar (Assembly constituency)|Jaswantnagar]] \n| term_start12 = 1974\n| term_end12 = 1980\n| predecessor12     = Bishambhar Singh Yadav\n| successor12       = [[Balram Singh Yadav]] \n| constituency12 = [[Jaswantnagar (Assembly constituency)|Jaswantnagar]] \n| term_start13 = 1985\n| term_end13 = 1996\n| predecessor13     = [[Balram Singh Yadav]] \n| successor13       = [[Shivpal Singh Yadav]] \n| constituency13 = [[Jaswantnagar (Assembly constituency)|Jaswantnagar]] \n| party            = [[Samajwadi Party]] (1992-present)\n| otherparty = * [[Socialist Party (India)|Socialist Party]]\n* [[Bharatiya Lok Dal]]\n* [[Janata Party]]\n* Lok Dal (B)\n* [[Janata Dal]]\n| spouse           = (1) Malati Devi (2) Sadhana Gupta\n| children         = [[Akhilesh Yadav]], Prateek Yadav\n| footnotes        = \n| relations        = [[Ram Gopal Yadav]] (cousin)<br>[[Shivpal Singh Yadav]] (brother)<br />[[Dimple Yadav]] (daughter-in-law)<br />\nKamla Devi Yadav (sister) <br />[[Dharmendra Yadav]] (nephew)<br />[[Akshay Yadav]] (nephew)<br />[[Tej Pratap Singh Yadav]] (grandnephew)<br />Apana Yadav (daughter-in-law)\n| alma_mater = [[Karm Kshetra Post Graduate College|K. K. College, Etawah]]<br>A.K. College, Shikohabad<br>B.R. College<br>[[Agra University]]\n| education = [[Master of Arts]] \n| profession = [[Agriculturist]] \n| occupation = [[Politician]] \n}}\n\n'''Mulayam Singh Yadav''' (born 22 November 1939) is an Indian politician from [[Uttar Pradesh]] and the founder-patron of the [[Samajwadi Party]]. He served for three non-consecutive terms as the [[Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh]] from 1989 to 1991, 1993 to 1995, and 2003 to 2007 respectively and also served as the [[Minister of Defence (India)|Minister of Defence]] from 1996 to 1998 in the [[United Front]] government. He has also served as the [[Member of Parliament]] in the [[Lok Sabha]] from [[Azamgarh (Lok Sabha constituency)|Azamgarh]] between 2014 and 2019. He is currently the [[Member of Parliament]], representing the constituency of [[Mainpuri]] in the lower house.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lok Sabha member profile|url=http://164.100.47.132/lssnew/Members/Biography.aspx?mpsno=530|publisher=Lok Sabha|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201161621/http://164.100.47.132/LssNew/Members/Biography.aspx?mpsno=530|archivedate=1 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMulayam Singh Yadav was born to Murti Devi and Sughar Singh Yadav on 22 November 1939 in [[Saifai village]], [[Etawah district]], Uttar Pradesh, India.<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web |title=Detailed Profile: Shri Mulayam Singh Yadav |publisher=Government of India |url=http://india.gov.in/my-government/indian-parliament/mulayam-singh-yadav |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\nYadav has three degrees\u2014B.A., B.T. and M.A. in political science from [[Karm Kshetra Post Graduate College]] in [[Etawah]], A. K. College in [[Shikohabad]], and B. R. College, [[Dr. B. R. Ambedkar University|Agra University]] respectively.<ref name=\"profile\" />\n\nYadav has married twice. His first wife Malti Devi suffered complications while giving birth to their first child, Akhilesh. She was in a vegetative state until May 2003 when she died. [[Akhilesh Yadav]], went on to become the [[Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh]] from 2012 to 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/the-samajwadi-parivar/921192/0 |title=The Samajwadi Parivar |work=Indian Express |date=7 March 2012 |accessdate=2013-10-10 |last=Yadav |first=Shyamlal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2003-05-27/lucknow/27270264_1_tributes-saifai-village-mulayam-singh-yadav |title=Tributes paid to Mulayam's wife |work=The Times of India |accessdate=2013-10-10}}</ref> Yadav had a relationship with Sadhana Gupta while still married to Malti Devi in the 1980s and the couple had a son named Prateek in 1988. Gupta was not well known until February 2007, when the relationship was admitted in [[Supreme Court of India|India's Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/mar/06spec.htm |title=Will this man bring down Mulayam? |last=Bhatt |first=Sheela |date=6 March 2007 |accessdate=2007-10-10 |work=rediff.com}}</ref> Prateek Yadav manages the land-holdings of the Yadav family.<ref name=\"prateekyadav\">{{cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/mulayam-s-younger-son-prefers-bodybuilding-to-body-politic/1061986/0 |title=Mulayam\u2019s younger son prefers body-building to body politic |date=20 January 2013 |accessdate=2013-10-10 |work=Indian Express}}</ref>\n\n== Early political career ==\n\nGroomed by leaders such as [[Ram Manohar Lohia]] and [[Raj Narain]], Yadav was first elected as a [[Member of the Legislative Assembly]] in [[Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]] in 1967. Yadav served eight terms there. In 1975, during [[Indira Gandhi|Indira Gandhi's]] imposition of the Emergency, Mulayam Yadav was arrested and kept in custody for 19 months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caravanmagazine.in/reportage/everybodys-brother-akhilesh-yadav|title=Akhilesh Yadav in the family business|last=Dixit|first=Neha|website=The Caravan|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>  He first became a state minister in 1977. Later, in 1980, he became the president of the [[Lok Dal]] (People's Party) in Uttar Pradesh which became a part of the [[Janata Dal]] (People's Party) afterwards.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} In 1982, he was elected leader of the opposition in the [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Council]] and held that post until 1985.<ref name=\"profile\" /> When the Lok Dal party split, Yadav launched the [[Krantikari Morcha]] party.<ref name=a>{{cite book|title=Business Standard Political Profiles of Cabals and Kings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qT7QvviGoJsC&pg=PA47|year=2009|publisher=Business Standard Books|isbn=978-81-905735-4-2|page=47}}</ref>\n\n==Chief Minister==\n=== First term ===\nYadav first became Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh in 1989.<ref name=\"profile\" />\n\nAfter the collapse of the [[V. P. Singh]] national government in November 1990, Yadav joined [[Chandra Shekhar]]'s Janata Dal (Socialist) party and continued in office as chief minister with the support of the [[Indian National Congress]] (INC). His government fell when the INC withdrew their support in April 1991 in the aftermath of developments at the national level where it has earlier withdrawn its support for Chandra Shekhar's government. Mid-term elections to Uttar Pradesh assembly were held in mid-1991, in which Mulayam Singh's party lost power to the [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n=== Second term ===\nIn 1992, Yadav founded his own Samajwadi Party (Socialist Party).<ref name=\"profile\" /> In 1993, he allied with the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] for the elections to Uttar Pradesh assembly due to be held in November 1993. The alliance between Samajwadi Party and Bahujan Samaj Party prevented the return of BJP to power in the state. Yadav became chief minister<ref name=\"profile\" /> of Uttar Pradesh with the support of Congress and Janata Dal. His stand on movement for demanding separate statehood for [[Uttarakhand]] was as much controversial as his stand on Ayodhya movement in 1990 was. There was a firing on Uttarakhand activists at Muzaffarnagar on 2 October 1994, something for which Uttarakhand activists held him responsible. He continued holding that post until his ally opted into another alliance in June 1998.\n\n=== Third term  ===\nIn 2002, following a fluid post-election situation in Uttar Pradesh, the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] and Bahujan Samaj Party joined to form a government under Dalit leader [[Mayawati]], who was considered to be Yadav's greatest political rival in the state.<ref name=\"foe\">{{cite web|title=Mulayam may be keen to shake hands with Maya, but is she?|url=http://www.dailyo.in/politics/mulayam-singh-yadav-mayawati-samajwadi-party-bsp-up-polls-bihar-polls/story/1/7453.html|website=www.dailyo.in|accessdate=2016-07-05}}</ref> The BJP pulled out of the government on 25 August 2003, and enough rebel legislators of the Bahujan Samaj Party left to allow Yadav to become the Chief Minister, with the support of independents and small parties.<ref name=\"rediff\">{{cite web|title=UP governor invites Mulayam to form government|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2003/aug/28up.htm|website=www.rediff.com|accessdate=2016-07-05}}</ref> He was sworn in as chief minister of Uttar Pradesh for the third time in September 2003.<ref name=\"profile\" /> It is widely believed that this change was done with the blessings of the BJP, which was also ruling at the Centre then.<ref name=\"rediff\"/>\n\nYadav was still a member of the Lok Sabha when he was sworn in as chief minister. In order to meet the constitutional requirement of becoming the member of state legislature within six months of being sworn in, he contested the assembly by-election from [[Gunnaur]] assembly seat in January 2004. Yadav won by a record margin, polling almost 94 per cent of the votes.<ref name=\"zeeen\">{{cite news|title=Gunnaur voters feel Mulayam may not retain seat|url=http://zeenews.india.com/home/gunnaur-voters-feel-mulayam-may-not-retain-seat_364874.html|accessdate=2016-07-05|date=8 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nWith the hope of playing a major role at the centre, Yadav contested the 2004 Lok Sabha elections from Mainpuri while still Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh. He won the seat and his Samajwadi Party won more seats in Uttar Pradesh than all other parties.{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}} However the Congress party, which formed the coalition government at the centre after the elections, had majority in the Lok Sabha with the support of the Communist parties. As a result, Yadav could not play any significant role at the centre, Yadav resigned from the Lok Sabha and chose to continue as chief minister of Uttar Pradesh{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} until the 2007 elections, when he lost to the BSP.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Mulayam-concedes-defeat-its-Maya-in-UP/articleshow/2031046.cms? |title=Mulayam concedes defeat, it's Maya in UP |work=The Times of India |date=11 May 2007 |accessdate=2016-09-21}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014 Indian General Election ===\nYadav and other members of the SP were criticised for conducting a festival during a crisis following riots in [[Muzzafarnagar]], Uttar Pradesh.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tehelka.com/the-neros-of-uttar-pradesh-2/ |title=The Neros Of Uttar Pradesh |publisher=Tehelka Magazine |date=18 January 2014 |accessdate=2014-03-04 |first=Deevakar |last=Anand}}</ref> He and his party formed a pre-poll alliance for the 2014 Indian General Election that involved ten other parties.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/elections/article/election-2014/nitish-kumar-mulayam-singh-yadav-in-11-party-front-to-battle-congress-bjp-in-lok-sabha-polls-488230 |title=Nitish Kumar, Mulayam Singh Yadav in 11-party front to battle Congress, BJP in Lok Sabha polls |publisher=NDTV |date=25 February 2014 |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> He was elected as a member of the [[16th Lok Sabha]] in those elections from two constituencies - Azamgarh and Manipuri - and subsequently resigned the latter seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=BJP now eyes Mulayam Singh Yadav's Mainpuri seat |date=27 May 2014 |work=The Asian Age |url=http://www.asianage.com/india/bjp-now-eyes-mulayam-singh-yadavs-mainpuri-seat-394 |accessdate=2014-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.india.com/news/india/mulayam-singh-yadav-meets-uttar-pradesh-governor-ram-naik-400169/|title=Mulayam Singh Yadav meets Uttar Pradesh Governor Ram Naik|agency=Press Trust of India|work=India.com|accessdate=2015-09-04}}</ref>\n\nThe only other successful SP candidates in the election were relatives of Yadav: his daughter-in-law, [[Dimple Yadav]], his nephews [[Dharmendra Yadav]] and [[Akshay Yadav]] and his grand-nephew [[Tej Pratap Singh Yadav]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://164.100.47.132/LssNew/Members/statedetail.aspx?state_code=Uttar%20Pradesh|title=Lok Sabha|work=47.132|accessdate=2015-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==Cabinet minister==\nIn 1996, Yadav was elected to the eleventh [[Lok Sabha]] from Mainpuri constituency.<ref name=\"profile\" /> In the United Front coalition government formed that year, his party joined and he was named India's [[Minister of Defence (India)|Defence Minister]].<ref name=\"profile\" /> That government fell in 1998 as India went in for fresh elections, but he returned to the Lok Sabha that year<ref name=\"profile\" /> from [[Sambhal]] parliamentary constituency. After the fall of [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]] government at the centre in April 1999, he did not support the Congress party in the formation of the government at the Centre. He contested Lok Sabha elections of 1999 from two seats, Sambhal and [[Kannauj]], and won from both. He resigned from Kannauj seat for his son Akhilesh in the by-elections.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n== Controversies ==\n=== Criticism over comment on rape ===\nThe crime of rape became a capital offence in India following the [[2012 Delhi gang rape]] incident. Yadav has opposed this change in the law, saying that \"Boys will be boys. Boys commit mistakes\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Burke |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/31/india-gang-rape-katra-sadatgunj-fathyer-speaks |title='Go to the mango trees,' the bereaved father was told. 'The body of your daughter is there' |work=The Observer |date=31 May 2014 |accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref> In response to [[2014 Badaun gang rape]] and Yadav's comments, UN Secretary-General [[Ban Ki-moon]] said \u201cWe say no to the dismissive, destructive attitude of, 'Boys will be boys'\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/717810/ally-of-indias-modi-says-rape-sometimes-right-sometimes-wrong/ |title=Ally of India\u2019s Modi says rape \"sometimes right, sometimes wrong\" |work=The Express Tribune |date=5 June 2014 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref> On 19 August 2015, Yadav remarked that gang-rapes are impractical and rape-victims in those cases tend to lie.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Activists-leaders-slam-Mulayam-Singh-for-saying-gang-rape-is-impractical/articleshow/48540988.cms|title=Activists, leaders slam Mulayam Singh for saying 'gang rape is impractical'|work=The Times of India|accessdate=2015-09-04}}</ref> He was summonsed by the judicial magistrate of [[Kulpahar]] court in Uttar Pradesh for that remark.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/up-court-summons-mulayam-singh-over-rape-remark/article7566027.ece|title=UP court summons Mulayam Singh over rape remark|first=Mohammad |last=Ali|work=The Hindu|accessdate=2015-09-04}}</ref>\n\n=== Support for a sovereign independent Tibet ===\nYadav has said it is necessary for India to support a [[sovereign]] and independent [[Tibet]]. He said that a past government had made a \u201cbig mistake\u201d on the issue and noted that he had spoken against it at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/china-ready-to-attack-india-claims-mulayam-in-lok-sabha/articleshow/59663877.cms |title=Mulayam Singh Yadav: China ready to attack India, claims Mulayam in Lok Sabha |work=The Times of India |date=2017-07-19 |accessdate=2018-01-02}}</ref> He believed that Tibet was a traditional buffer between China and India<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/mulayam-singh-yadavs-surprise-revelation-china-has-buried-nuclear-bombs-in-pakistan-nehru-erred-on-tibet/770060/ |title=Mulayam Singh Yadav's surprise 'revelation': China has buried nuclear bombs in Pakistan, Nehru erred on Tibet |work=The Financial Express |date=2017-07-19 |accessdate=2018-01-02}}</ref> and that India should support the [[Dalai Lama]] and Tibetan independence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/china-ready-to-attack-india-mulayam-claims-in-lok-sabha/article19307967.ece |title=China ready to attack India, Mulayam Singh Yadav claims in Lok Sabha |work=The Hindu |date= |accessdate=2018-01-02}}</ref> Claiming that China had secreted nuclear weapons in Pakistan, he cautioned that \u201cChina is our enemy, not Pakistan. Pakistan can do us no damage\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/china-buried-nuclear-weapons-in-pakistan-to-attack-india-says-mulayam-singh-yadav/1/1005789.html |title=China has buried nukes in Pakistan to attack India: Former Defence Minister Mulayam Singh Yadav |work=India Today |date=2017-07-19 |accessdate=2018-01-02}}</ref>\n=== Family feud ===\nSince the young Akhilesh Yadav became Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh in 2012, surpassing Mulayam's brother [[Shivpal Singh Yadav]], the Yadav family was divided into two feuding groups. One of the groups, led by Akhilesh, enjoyed the support of his father's cousin and National General Secretary [[Ram Gopal Yadav]]. The rival group was led by Mulayam Singh and supported by his brother and State Chief of Party, Shivpal Yadav, and a friend, MP [[Amar Singh (politician)|Amar Singh]]. Akhilesh had fired his uncle twice from his cabinet as it was seen by many as a direct challenge to his father, who has steadily supported Shivpal over Akhilesh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/53902522.cms|title=Infighting erupts in ruling Yadav family in UP, Mulayam continues to pull the power strings|last=Rai|first=Manmohan|date=|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> On 30 December 2016, Mulayam Yadav expelled his son Akhilesh and his cousin Ram Gopal from the party for six years on the grounds of indiscipline, only to revoke the decision 24 hours later. Akhilesh, in response, stripped his father off the party presidency and instead named him the chief patron of the party following the national convention of the party on 1 January 2017. Mulayam termed the national convention as illegal and directly expelled his cousin, Ram Gopal Yadav, who had convened the national executive convention. But the Election commission of India ruled that Ram Gopal Yadav had the right to convene that executive convention, and reversed Mulayam's order. Hence Akhilesh Yadav officially became the new National Leader of the party.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book|title=India's silent revolution: Rise of lower castes in North India|year=2003|last=Jaffrelot|first=Christophe |authorlink=Christophe Jaffrelot |publisher=C. Hurst & Co. |isbn=978-1-85065-670-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-rMW03l_gx0C}}\n*{{cite book |title=Business Standard Political Profiles: Of Cabals and Kings |author=[[Aditi Phadnis]] |publisher=Business Standard Books |year=2009 |isbn=9788190573542 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qT7QvviGoJsC}}\n*{{cite book |title=News As Culture: Journalistic Practices and the Remaking of Indian Leadership Tradition |first=Ursula |last=Rao |publisher=Berghahn Books |year=2010 |isbn=9781845456696 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6KsXVHAUWNwC}}\n*{{cite book |title=Theft of an Idol: Text and Context in the Representation of Collective Violence |first=Paul R. |last=Brass |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=1997 |isbn=9780691026503 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q55rb_-NnugC}}\n*{{cite book |title=Contesting the Nation: Religion, Community, and the Politics of Democracy in India |editor-first=David E. |editor-last=Ludden |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |year=1996 |isbn=9780812215854 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jEUdPqYQjhoC}}\n*{{cite book |title=Mulayam Singh: a political biography |first1=Ram |last1=Singh |first2=Anshuman |last2=Yadav |publisher=Konark Publishers |year=1998 |isbn=9788122005301}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.samajwadiparty.in/ourleader-mulayam.html Profile on Samajwadi Party website]\n\n{{Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{16th LS members from Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=Mulayam Singh Yadav}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Samajwadi Party]] in the [[16th Lok Sabha]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yadav, Mulayam Singh}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People born in Saifai]]\n[[Category:11th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:12th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:13th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:14th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Defence Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar University alumni]]\n[[Category:15th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:17th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:V. P. Singh administration]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh MLAs 1977\u20131980]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh MLAs 1989\u20131991]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh MLAs 1993\u20131996]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:16th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition in the Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]